{"title_page": "Dirndl", "text_new": "{{short description|Traditional dress worn in Germany,\u00a0Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria and South Tyrol}}\n[[File:Dirndl.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n[[File:KurzsDiandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Seated women wearing modern dirndls.]]\n[[File:Diandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Different colour variations can depend on the origin of the woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n\nA '''dirndl''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8d\u026a\u0281ndl\u0329|lang|De-at-Dirndl.ogg}},<ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.com/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref><ref name=\"auto11\"></{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/08/german-beer-maid-costume.html|title=German Beer Maid Costume|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref> {{lang-bar|Diandl}}) <ref name=\"auto11\"/> is the name of a traditional feminine [[dress]] worn in [[Austria]], [[South Tyrol]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is based on the traditional clothing of [[Alps]] peasants.<ref name=\"auto10\"/><ref>''Ethnic Dress in the United States: A Cultural Encyclopedia'', eds. Annette Lynch; Mitchell D. Strauss (Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield, 2015), p. 100</ref><ref name=\"austria.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412041607/http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |archivedate=2015-04-12 }}</ref>  Dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as {{lang|de|Landhausmode}} ('country-inspired fashion').\n\nA '''dirndl skirt''' generally describes a light circular cut dress, gathered at the waist, that falls below the knee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dirndl Skirts|first=Alice|last=Watt|date=26 April 2012|url=http://www.elleuk.com/fashion/what-to-wear/dirndl-skirts#image=1|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|location=London|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spin out with springtime's dirndl skirt|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/fashion/spin-out-with-springtimes-dirndl-skirt-7722321.html|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|first=Karen|last=Dacre|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe dirndl consists of a [[bodice]] and skirt or a pinafore dress, a low-cut [[blouse]] with short puff sleeves, full [[skirt]] and [[apron]].<ref name=\"onesprime.de\">{{cite news|url=|title=Oktoberfest Dirndl dress: the bow|last=|first=|date=|website=Onesprime.de|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destination-munich.com/german-dirndl.html |title=German Dirndl - an illustrated guide |website=Destination-munich.com |date=2017-03-25 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://ladyandtherose.com/2012/09/21/how-to-wear-a-dirndl/ |title=How to wear a dirndl &#124; The Lady & the Rose |website=Ladyandtherose.com |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> While appearing to be simple and plain, a properly made modern dirndl may be quite expensive as it is tailored, and sometimes cut from costly hand-printed or silk fabrics.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\"/>\n\nThe winter style dirndl has heavy, warm skirts and aprons made of thick [[cotton]], [[linen]], [[velvet]] or [[wool]], and long sleeves. The colors are usually rich and dark. The summer style is lighter and more revealing, has short sleeves, and is often made of lightweight cotton.\n\nAccessories may include a long apron tied round the waist, a [[waistcoat]] or a wool [[shawl]]. In many regions, especially the [[Altaussee|Ausseerland]], vibrantly colored, hand-printed silk scarfs and silk aprons are worn. Women often wear necklaces, earrings and brooches made of silver, the antlers of deer or even animals' teeth. For colder weather there are heavy dirndl coats in the same cut as the dresses, with a high neck and front buttons, thick mittens and wool hats.\n\nDifferent [[Fashion|styles]] were worn in different regions,<ref name=\"austria.info\"/> but they are now more universally generalized.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/>\n\n===Dirndl vs. Tracht and traditional folk costumes===\n[[File:Schwarzwaelderin in Tracht um 1900.jpg|thumb|150px|The female ''[[Tracht]]'' of [[Gutach (Schwarzwaldbahn)|Gutach]] in the [[Black Forest]], around 1900. The red colour of the pompons indicates that the woman was unmarried.]]\n\nThe typical dirndl and folk costume varies from one region, or even village, to another. Folk costume has various details according to the place of origin and social status of the wearer. The modern dirndl is heavily stylized but clearly influenced by typical Bavarian costume. There is also a distinction between the typical dirndl (that is, a garment with an apron made of material with traditional patterns and embroidery) and rural domestic clothing, made from gray or colored linen, sometimes with leather bodice and trim.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 119-5592-12A, M\u00e4dchen mit spielenden Kindern.jpg|thumb|200px|A dirndl on a German young girl in 1933.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe dirndl originated as a more hardy form of the costume worn today: the uniform of Austrian [[domestic worker]]s during  the 19th century . Simple forms were also worn commonly by working women in plain colors or a simple check. The Austrian upper classes adopted the dirndl as high fashion in the 1870s, making it a highly fashionable and popular must-have item in the nation soon after.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBoth skirts and pinafore dresses with vest-shaped tank tops, cooking aprons and blouses were commonplace in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe basic blouse/skirt/corset idea came from the eastern regions of the [[Swiss Alps]], and was originally simple rural clothing. It became female Austrian servants' [[work clothes]] as well as Alpine peasant attire in the 18th century and exclusively servant\u2019s work clothes in the 19th century.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAustrian [[Emperor Franz Joseph]] and his wife [[Elisabeth of Bavaria]] liked rustic clothing called a 'Sissi', which equates to what the normal folk called a 'dirndl'.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Development of the dirndl as a fashion mode===\n\nIt appeared in its current state of decorative format and style in eastern Switzerland in the 1890s, and spread in the early 20th century<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\">[https://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html#35 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111201/http://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html |date=2013-05-06 }}</ref> to the south of Germany, Austria, Liechtenstein,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/> South Tirol, Trentino and Valcanale Friuli.\n   \nA decisive influence in the development of the dirndl to a fashion mode came from the Jewish brothers Moritz and Julius Wallach (originally from Bielefeld in north-western Germany), who in 1890 founded the M\u00fcnchner Volkskunsthaus (Munich house of folk culture). \nTheir seamstresses industriously produced the first elegant tracht dresses from colourful printed fabrics, predominantly silk. These were first exhibited by company models at summer parties in the Alps. The breakthrough came in 1910, when the Wallach brothers organized and paid for the show of folk costumes for the centenary celebrations of the Oktoberfest.<ref> Heidi Hagen-Pekdemir: Bielefelder machten das Dirndl erst schick. In: Neue Westf\u00e4lische, 30. September 2015. </ref>\n\n[[File:Volksfestumzug in Vilshofen a.d. Donau 2012 (3).JPG|thumb|200px|Historically derived modern children's dirndl at a Volksfestumzug in [[Vilshofen an der Donau]] in 2012]]\n\n===Nazi period===\n\nDuring the [[Nazi]] period, the [[Mittelstelle]] German costume of National Socialist Women of the \"[[Reich Commissioner for costume work]]\" was established under [[Gertrud Pesendorfer]].<ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uibk.ac.at/geschichte-ethnologie/ee/trachten/projekt.html |title=Projekt \u2013 Universit\u00e4t Innsbruck |website=Uibk.ac.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> In the context of Nazi ideology her designs represented \"renewed costume\".<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref>\n\nThe \"de-catholicised\" <ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wolfgangboehmer.com/komposition/oper-1/jedermann/|title=Jedermann - Rockoper|website=Wolfgang Boehmer komposition arrangement libretto}}</ref>(''entkatholisiert'')<ref name=\"auto9\" /> style became popular as the Dirndl was de-collared (''de-Cocratisiert'')<!--{{Citation needed|reason=This word doesn't seem to exist outside of this article. I checked several dictionaries, Google ngrams and the first results of a duck duck go search|date=June 2017}}--> (ie: the closed collars removed so it could gain an erotic [[decollete]] collar and\\or off-the-shoulders neckline), the skirt was slightly shortened and the women's arms were no longer  covered beyond the elbow, and it was thus modernized and romanticized as well as eroticized.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\"/> Gertrud Pesendorfer's declared goal was to free the costume of \"overburdening by church, industrialization and fashionable cries\" and \"foreign influences\" and to let the \"rogue sub-culture\" back again.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===After the Second World War===\n\nDirndls and ''Landhausmode'' were abandoned for a while after World War II. While the wearing of the corresponding garments was scarcely popular in the 1970s, it has grown strongly since the 1990s.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echoonline.at/hauptnews-detail/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=4528&cHash=7ffe5edd560b21deb88d5b10f68e12ee |title=HauptNews Detail |website=Echoonline.at |date=2013-10-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1389858057909/Von-Dirndln-Trachten-und-Akademikerbaellen |title=Von Dirndln, Trachten und Akademikerb\u00e4llen - Kommentare der anderen - derStandard.at \u203a Meinung |website=Derstandard.at |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\"/>\n\nIn the 21st century, fashion designers have adopted the dirndl, with varying results.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> It has become a popular Upper Tyrol and Bavarian fashion<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VDN1ve_5d-Q|title=The Dirndl Folk Dress - euromaxx|last=DW (English)|date=10 September 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XzktIfPQY&NR=1&featureendscreen|title=Perfektes Dirndl-Dekollet\u00e9: Die modischen Tricks f\u00fcr die Wiesn-Tracht|date=25 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and regular party outfit during [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://signora-moda.de/category/kleidung/tracht/|title=Tracht - Signora e la Moda|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book | last=Schmidt | first=Maximilian |date=1902 | title=Meine Wanderung durch 70 Jahre. Zweiter Teil |language=German | location=Reutlingen |publisher=En\u00dflin & Laiblin | pages=247\u2013260 | isbn= }}</ref> \n.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|title=Oktoberfest|url=http://www.spatenbeer.com/lessons-oktoberfest.html|publisher=Spaten|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|title=10 Things you didn't know about Oktoberfest|url=http://www.costumecrazy.com.au/blog/blog-posts/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-oktoberfest/|website=Costume Crazy|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lostgirlsworld.com/2011/04/dirndl/|title=How To Wear a Traditional Bavarian Dirndl - The Lost Girls|website=www.lostgirlsworld.com}}</ref> The ''Dirndlkjoler'' is more common here{{where?|date=August 2017}} with short skirts, bodice just reaching to below the breasts, and dirndl-blouses with deep neckline and bare shoulders. There are also push-up bras that lift and collect the bust at the neckline.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn Switzerland, the dirndl is the official outfit for certain representations, events, cultural shows and singing old folk songs often involving yodeling.<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174|title=What are the Swiss traditional clothes?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nToday, dirndls vary from simple off-the-shelf styles to exquisitely crafted, very expensive models.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe scruffy, sexed-up, open-collar, or economy versions and disjointed dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as ''Landhausmode'' (literally \"country house style\") dresses.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sommerdirndl.com/ |title=Sommerdirndl |publisher=Sommerdirndl |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bavaria-lederhosen.com/en/top-suchbegriffe/ ]{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/262-trachten-wear/283-children/285-girls/heidi-dirndl.html |title=Buy Heidi Red Dirndl Online &#124; Germany &#124; Ernst Licht, USA |website=Ernstlicht.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.dirndl.com/ |title=Dirndl.com - Original Bavarian Oktoberfest Dirndl Dress and Lederhosen |website=Usa.dirndl.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerstins-landhausmode.com/children_clothes.htm |title=Children |website=Kerstins-landhausmode.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bavarian-superstore.de/ |title=Bavarian Superstore, Einkaufen wie Gott in Bayern |language=de|website=Bavarian-superstore.de |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesnkoenig-usa.com/dirndl |title=Dirndl |publisher=Wiesnkoenig USA |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> The children's version is called '' M\u00e4dchenkleid'' (girl's dress). \n\nThese are closed-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/media/catalog/product/cache/1/image/9df78eab33525d08d6e5fb8d27136e95/h/e/heidi-dirndl_new_site.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\"/> and these are open-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-1O1QKrMxngw/U6cS5JKXB5I/AAAAAAAAAR0/WiaeneAYTt4/s1600/dirndl1.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk/2014/06/fashion-dirndl-dress.html |title=Fashion Design: Fashion dirndl Dress |website=Amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nGermany and Austria have many manufacturers of the outfits. Both the open-collar and closed-collar versions are popular in those countries. ''Eisbergkleider'' are less popular in North America than in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mydirndl.com/|title=Dirndl & Lederhosen Imported from Germany & Beyond|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Austria, and other parts of south central Europe, there are literally splashy events known as Dirndlspringen, in which people, often attractive young women, are judged by how well they dive from a diving board into a lake or a swimming pool while wearing the dirndl, using it as a swimdress. Many examples of Dirndlspringen events are found on YouTube.\n\n===North American usage===\nGermans, Austrian, Swiss and Scandinavians people migrated to North America in the 19th century. Germans made a strong contribution to the gene pool of Montana, Minnesota, the Dakotas, Missouri, Wisconsin, New York City <ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.germany.travel/en/ms/german-originality/german-clubs/german-clubs.html|title=German Clubs across America|first=Deutsche Zentrale f\u00fcr Tourismus|last=e.V.|publisher=}}</ref> and Chicago. The [[German American]] ethnic group (German: Deutschamerikaner) are their descendants in north America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr|title=memoria.ro - bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103|last=Aspera|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA153&lpg=RA2-PA153&dq=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse#v=onepage&q=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse&f=false|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe [4 volumes]: American Fashion from Head to Toe|first1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco|last1=F|first2=Patricia Kay|last2=Hunt-Hurst|first3=Heather Vaughan|last3=Lee|first4=Mary|last4=Doering|date=23 November 2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books|isbn=9781610693103}}</ref> Beginning in 1920 and especially after World War II, many [[Danube Swabians]] migrated to the United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, Austria, Australia, and Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr |title=bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103 |website=Memoria.ro |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAcross the United States there are dozens of German-American cultural or heritage clubs, such as the Donauschwaben<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-25|title=Danube Swabians|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Danube_Swabians&oldid=761981460|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref> heritage clubs.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In these clubs, members host events and festivals to preserve and/or celebrate their heritage with the surrounding communities. During these festivals, participants often dress in traditional outfits such as dirndls and [[lederhosen]].\n\n==Name==\nIn the South German dialects ([[Austro-Bavarian|Bairisch]]), ''Dirndl'' originally referred to a young woman or a girl, while the word ''Dirndlgewand'' referred to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hCbTfFKEUUgC&pg=PA106|title=Munique e Arredores: Alemanha! Por que n\u00e3o?|first=Angela|last=Arten-Meyer|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Books on Demand|via=Google Books|isbn=9783842359796}}</ref> Nowadays, ''Dirndl'' may equally refer to either a young woman or to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> ''Dirndl'' is a diminutive form of the dated word ''Dirn(e)'' for \"girl\"; in the 20th century, ''Dirne'' (originally a euphemism) has also developed towards meaning \"prostitute\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The word is ''Dirn'' in standardized  German  and ''Deern'' in  Low Saxon.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/>\n\n==Dressing etiquette==\nThe dirndl is mostly worn in [[Austria]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is used as an everyday dress primarily by older women in rural areas. Other women may wear it at formal occasions (much like a [[Scotland|Scotsman]] wearing a [[kilt]]) and during certain traditional events. It is hugely popular also among young women at the time of a ''[[Volksfest]]'', such as the [[Oktoberfest]] in [[Munich]] (and similar festivals),<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/> although many women will only wear dirndl-style dresses, called ''Landhausmode'', which may deviate in numerous ways and are often much cheaper.\n\nIn Austria and Bavaria, the dirndl may often be seen on women working in tourism-related businesses, and sometimes waitresses in traditional-style restaurants or [[beer garden]]s. It is also seen in these regions on women in the ''[[Volksmusik]]'' business.\n\nThere is an [[urban legend]] that claims the placement of the [[knot]] on the apron is an indicator of the woman's marital status.<ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/09/germany-oktoberfest-dirndl-fashion/406294/|title=You're Wearing Your Oktoberfest Dress Wrong|last=Horn|first=Heather|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref>  In this story, which is not based in tradition, tying the sash on the woman's left side indicates that she is single, and a knot tied on the right means that she is married, engaged or otherwise not interested in dating.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Dirndl Code: Expert Tips for a Rollicking Oktoberfest|first=Julia|last=Stanek|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/expert-tips-how-to-get-the-most-out-of-oktoberfest-a-922991.html|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=18 September 2013|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|location=Hamburg}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/>\n\n==Films featuring women in dirndl costumes==\n{{see also|Heimatfilm}}\n\n*''[[Almost Angels]]''\n*''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]''\n*''[[Heidi]]'' ([[Heidi (1937 film)|1937]] and [[Heidi (1968 film)|1968]])\n*''[[National Lampoon's European Vacation]]'' \n*''[[The Producers (1967 film)|The Producers]]''\n*''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''\n*''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''\n*''[[The Student Prince]]''\n*''[[The Witch (2015 film)|The Witch]]'' \n*''[[Young Frankenstein]]''\n*''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]''\n\n==Musical mentions of dirndls==\n*The dirndl is mentioned in the song \"Turn Around\", composed in 1959 by [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Alan Greene]], and [[Malvina Reynolds]]. \"Dirndls and petticoats, where have you gone?\"  This song was originally recorded by the [[Kingston Trio]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dirndl}}\n{{portal|Austria|Germany|Switzerland}}\n* [[Pinafore]]\n* [[Pinafore dress]]\n* [[Lederhosen]]\n* [[Tracht]]\n* [[Bild Lilli doll]]\n* [[Folk costume]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gexi Tostmann: ''Das Dirndl (Alpenl\u00e4ndische Tradition und Mode)''. Verlag Christian Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 1998\n* Heide Hollmer, Kathrin Hollmer: ''Dirndl. Trends, Traditionen, Philosophie, Pop, Stil, Styling''. Edition Ebersbach, Berlin 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-86915-043-7}}\n* Daniela M\u00fcller: ''Alles Dirndl.'' Anton Pustet Verlag, Salzburg 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7025-0693-3}}\n* Elisabeth Walln\u00f6fer: ''Geraubte Tradition. Wie die Nazis unsere Kultur verf\u00e4lschten.'' Sankt Ulrich, Augsburg 2011, {{ISBN|3867441944}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Dirndl}}\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n*https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174\n*[http://www.kfj.at/sites/thesite/dirndl.JPG image at an Austrian website]\n*[http://www.oldworldvillage.net/images/heidi/clothing/ladies/dirl3.jpg another image]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/officegeek/45002967/ modern dirndl]\n*[http://www.postrealism.com/dirndl.htm Photo and History of Dirndl Dress and Austrian Tracht]\n*[http://www.elsenaju.de/Mode/Trachten.htm Folk costume]\n*[https://www.mydirndl.com mydirndl.com] \n*[https://www.dirndl.com/en/ dirndl.com]\n*[https://www.oktoberfest.de/en/shop/tracht-for-women/dirndl-dresses/ oktoberfest.de]\n*[https://www.ernstlicht.com/12-ladies-clothing/97-ladies-dirndls ernstlicht.com]\n*[https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174 reference.com]\n\n{{Folk costume}}\n\n[[Category:1870s fashion]]\n[[Category:19th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:German clothing]]\n[[Category:Austrian clothing]]\n[[Category:Swiss clothing]]\n[[Category:Skirts]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:German culture]]\n[[Category:Austrian culture]]\n\n[[bar:Diandl]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Traditional dress worn in Germany,\u00a0Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria and South Tyrol}}\n[[File:Dirndl.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n[[File:KurzsDiandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Seated women wearing modern dirndls.]]\n[[File:Diandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Different colour variations can depend on the origin of the woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n\nA '''dirndl''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8d\u026a\u0281ndl\u0329|lang|De-at-Dirndl.ogg}},<ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.com/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref><ref name=\"auto11\"></{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/08/german-beer-maid-costume.html|title=German Beer Maid Costume|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref> {{lang-bar|Diandl}}) <ref name=\"auto11\"/> is the name of a traditional feminine [[dress]] worn in [[Austria]], [[South Tyrol]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is based on the traditional clothing of [[Alps]] peasants.<ref name=\"auto10\"/><ref>''Ethnic Dress in the United States: A Cultural Encyclopedia'', eds. Annette Lynch; Mitchell D. Strauss (Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield, 2015), p. 100</ref><ref name=\"austria.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412041607/http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |archivedate=2015-04-12 }}</ref>  Dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as {{lang|de|Landhausmode}} ('country-inspired fashion').\n\nA '''dirndl skirt''' generally describes a light circular cut dress, gathered at the waist, that falls below the knee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dirndl Skirts|first=Alice|last=Watt|date=26 April 2012|url=http://www.elleuk.com/fashion/what-to-wear/dirndl-skirts#image=1|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|location=London|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spin out with springtime's dirndl skirt|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/fashion/spin-out-with-springtimes-dirndl-skirt-7722321.html|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|first=Karen|last=Dacre|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe dirndl consists of a [[bodice]] and skirt or a pinafore dress, a low-cut [[blouse]] with short puff sleeves, full [[skirt]] and [[apron]].<ref name=\"onesprime.de\">{{cite news|url=|title=Oktoberfest Dirndl dress: the bow|last=|first=|date=|website=Onesprime.de|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destination-munich.com/german-dirndl.html |title=German Dirndl - an illustrated guide |website=Destination-munich.com |date=2017-03-25 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://ladyandtherose.com/2012/09/21/how-to-wear-a-dirndl/ |title=How to wear a dirndl &#124; The Lady & the Rose |website=Ladyandtherose.com |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> While appearing to be simple and plain, a properly made modern dirndl may be quite expensive as it is tailored, and sometimes cut from costly hand-printed or silk fabrics.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\"/>\n\nThe winter style dirndl has heavy, warm skirts and aprons made of thick [[cotton]], [[linen]], [[velvet]] or [[wool]], and long sleeves. The colors are usually rich and dark. The summer style is lighter and more revealing, has short sleeves, and is often made of lightweight cotton.\n\nAccessories may include a long apron tied round the waist, a [[waistcoat]] or a wool [[shawl]]. In many regions, especially the [[Altaussee|Ausseerland]], vibrantly colored, hand-printed silk scarfs and silk aprons are worn. Women often wear necklaces, earrings and brooches made of silver, the antlers of deer or even animals' teeth. For colder weather there are heavy dirndl coats in the same cut as the dresses, with a high neck and front buttons, thick mittens and wool hats.\n\nDifferent [[Fashion|styles]] were worn in different regions,<ref name=\"austria.info\"/> but they are now more universally generalized.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/>\n\n===Dirndl vs. Tracht and traditional folk costumes===\n[[File:Schwarzwaelderin in Tracht um 1900.jpg|thumb|150px|The female ''[[Tracht]]'' of [[Gutach (Schwarzwaldbahn)|Gutach]] in the [[Black Forest]], around 1900. The red colour of the pompons indicates that the woman was unmarried.]]\n\nThe typical dirndl and folk costume varies from one region, or even village, to another. Folk costume has various details according to the place of origin and social status of the wearer. The modern dirndl is heavily stylized but clearly influenced by typical Bavarian costume. There is also a distinction between the typical dirndl (that is, a garment with an apron made of material with traditional patterns and embroidery) and rural domestic clothing, made from gray or colored linen, sometimes with leather bodice and trim.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 119-5592-12A, M\u00e4dchen mit spielenden Kindern.jpg|thumb|200px|A dirndl on a German young girl in 1933.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe dirndl originated as a more hardy form of the costume worn today: the uniform of Austrian [[domestic worker]]s during  the 19th century . Simple forms were also worn commonly by working women in plain colors or a simple check. The Austrian upper classes adopted the dirndl as high fashion in the 1870s, making it a highly fashionable and popular must-have item in the nation soon after.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBoth skirts and pinafore dresses with vest-shaped tank tops, cooking aprons and blouses were commonplace in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe basic blouse/skirt/corset idea came from the eastern regions of the [[Swiss Alps]], and was originally simple rural clothing. It became female Austrian servants' [[work clothes]] as well as Alpine peasant attire in the 18th century and exclusively servant\u2019s work clothes in the 19th century.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAustrian [[Emperor Franz Joseph]] and his wife [[Elisabeth of Bavaria]] liked rustic clothing called a 'Sissi', which equates to what the normal folk called a 'dirndl'.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Development of the dirndl as a fashion mode===\n\nIt appeared in its current state of decorative format and style in eastern Switzerland in the 1890s, and spread in the early 20th century<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\">[https://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html#35 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111201/http://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html |date=2013-05-06 }}</ref> to the south of Germany, Austria, Liechtenstein,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/> South Tirol, Trentino and Valcanale Friuli.\n   \nA decisive influence in the development of the dirndl to a fashion mode came from the Jewish brothers Moritz and Julius Wallach (originally from Bielefeld in north-western Germany), who in 1890 founded the M\u00fcnchner Volkskunsthaus (Munich house of folk culture). \nTheir seamstresses industriously produced the first elegant tracht dresses from colourful printed fabrics, predominantly silk. These were first exhibited by company models at summer parties in the Alps. The breakthrough came in 1910, when the Wallach brothers organized and paid for the show of folk costumes for the centenary celebrations of the Oktoberfest.<ref> Heidi Hagen-Pekdemir: Bielefelder machten das Dirndl erst schick. In: Neue Westf\u00e4lische, 30. September 2015. </ref>\n\n\n[[File:Volksfestumzug in Vilshofen a.d. Donau 2012 (3).JPG|thumb|200px|Historically derived modern children's dirndl at a Volksfestumzug in [[Vilshofen an der Donau]] in 2012]]\n\n===Nazi period===\n\nDuring the [[Nazi]] period, the [[Mittelstelle]] German costume of National Socialist Women of the \"[[Reich Commissioner for costume work]]\" was established under [[Gertrud Pesendorfer]].<ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uibk.ac.at/geschichte-ethnologie/ee/trachten/projekt.html |title=Projekt \u2013 Universit\u00e4t Innsbruck |website=Uibk.ac.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> In the context of Nazi ideology her designs represented \"renewed costume\".<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref>\n\nThe \"de-catholicised\" <ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wolfgangboehmer.com/komposition/oper-1/jedermann/|title=Jedermann - Rockoper|website=Wolfgang Boehmer komposition arrangement libretto}}</ref>(''entkatholisiert'')<ref name=\"auto9\" /> style became popular as the Dirndl was de-collared (''de-Cocratisiert'')<!--{{Citation needed|reason=This word doesn't seem to exist outside of this article. I checked several dictionaries, Google ngrams and the first results of a duck duck go search|date=June 2017}}--> (ie: the closed collars removed so it could gain an erotic [[decollete]] collar and\\or off-the-shoulders neckline), the skirt was slightly shortened and the women's arms were no longer  covered beyond the elbow, and it was thus modernized and romanticized as well as eroticized.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\"/> Gertrud Pesendorfer's declared goal was to free the costume of \"overburdening by church, industrialization and fashionable cries\" and \"foreign influences\" and to let the \"rogue sub-culture\" back again.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===After the Second World War===\n\nDirndls and ''Landhausmode'' were abandoned for a while after World War II. While the wearing of the corresponding garments was scarcely popular in the 1970s, it has grown strongly since the 1990s.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echoonline.at/hauptnews-detail/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=4528&cHash=7ffe5edd560b21deb88d5b10f68e12ee |title=HauptNews Detail |website=Echoonline.at |date=2013-10-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1389858057909/Von-Dirndln-Trachten-und-Akademikerbaellen |title=Von Dirndln, Trachten und Akademikerb\u00e4llen - Kommentare der anderen - derStandard.at \u203a Meinung |website=Derstandard.at |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\"/>\n\nIn the 21st century, fashion designers have adopted the dirndl, with varying results.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> It has become a popular Upper Tyrol and Bavarian fashion<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VDN1ve_5d-Q|title=The Dirndl Folk Dress - euromaxx|last=DW (English)|date=10 September 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XzktIfPQY&NR=1&featureendscreen|title=Perfektes Dirndl-Dekollet\u00e9: Die modischen Tricks f\u00fcr die Wiesn-Tracht|date=25 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and regular party outfit during [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://signora-moda.de/category/kleidung/tracht/|title=Tracht - Signora e la Moda|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book | last=Schmidt | first=Maximilian |date=1902 | title=Meine Wanderung durch 70 Jahre. Zweiter Teil |language=German | location=Reutlingen |publisher=En\u00dflin & Laiblin | pages=247\u2013260 | isbn= }}</ref> \n.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|title=Oktoberfest|url=http://www.spatenbeer.com/lessons-oktoberfest.html|publisher=Spaten|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|title=10 Things you didn't know about Oktoberfest|url=http://www.costumecrazy.com.au/blog/blog-posts/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-oktoberfest/|website=Costume Crazy|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lostgirlsworld.com/2011/04/dirndl/|title=How To Wear a Traditional Bavarian Dirndl - The Lost Girls|website=www.lostgirlsworld.com}}</ref> The ''Dirndlkjoler'' is more common here{{where?|date=August 2017}} with short skirts, bodice just reaching to below the breasts, and dirndl-blouses with deep neckline and bare shoulders. There are also push-up bras that lift and collect the bust at the neckline.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn Switzerland, the dirndl is the official outfit for certain representations, events, cultural shows and singing old folk songs often involving yodeling.<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174|title=What are the Swiss traditional clothes?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nToday, dirndls vary from simple off-the-shelf styles to exquisitely crafted, very expensive models.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe scruffy, sexed-up, open-collar, or economy versions and disjointed dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as ''Landhausmode'' (literally \"country house style\") dresses.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sommerdirndl.com/ |title=Sommerdirndl |publisher=Sommerdirndl |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bavaria-lederhosen.com/en/top-suchbegriffe/ ]{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/262-trachten-wear/283-children/285-girls/heidi-dirndl.html |title=Buy Heidi Red Dirndl Online &#124; Germany &#124; Ernst Licht, USA |website=Ernstlicht.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.dirndl.com/ |title=Dirndl.com - Original Bavarian Oktoberfest Dirndl Dress and Lederhosen |website=Usa.dirndl.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerstins-landhausmode.com/children_clothes.htm |title=Children |website=Kerstins-landhausmode.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bavarian-superstore.de/ |title=Bavarian Superstore, Einkaufen wie Gott in Bayern |language=de|website=Bavarian-superstore.de |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesnkoenig-usa.com/dirndl |title=Dirndl |publisher=Wiesnkoenig USA |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> The children's version is called '' M\u00e4dchenkleid'' (girl's dress). \n\nThese are closed-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/media/catalog/product/cache/1/image/9df78eab33525d08d6e5fb8d27136e95/h/e/heidi-dirndl_new_site.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\"/> and these are open-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-1O1QKrMxngw/U6cS5JKXB5I/AAAAAAAAAR0/WiaeneAYTt4/s1600/dirndl1.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk/2014/06/fashion-dirndl-dress.html |title=Fashion Design: Fashion dirndl Dress |website=Amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nGermany and Austria have many manufacturers of the outfits. Both the open-collar and closed-collar versions are popular in those countries. ''Eisbergkleider'' are less popular in North America than in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mydirndl.com/|title=Dirndl & Lederhosen Imported from Germany & Beyond|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Austria, and other parts of south central Europe, there are literally splashy events known as Dirndlspringen, in which people, often attractive young women, are judged by how well they dive from a diving board into a lake or a swimming pool while wearing the dirndl, using it as a swimdress. Many examples of Dirndlspringen events are found on YouTube.\n\n===North American usage===\nGermans, Austrian, Swiss and Scandinavians people migrated to North America in the 19th century. Germans made a strong contribution to the gene pool of Montana, Minnesota, the Dakotas, Missouri, Wisconsin, New York City <ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.germany.travel/en/ms/german-originality/german-clubs/german-clubs.html|title=German Clubs across America|first=Deutsche Zentrale f\u00fcr Tourismus|last=e.V.|publisher=}}</ref> and Chicago. The [[German American]] ethnic group (German: Deutschamerikaner) are their descendants in north America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr|title=memoria.ro - bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103|last=Aspera|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA153&lpg=RA2-PA153&dq=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse#v=onepage&q=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse&f=false|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe [4 volumes]: American Fashion from Head to Toe|first1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco|last1=F|first2=Patricia Kay|last2=Hunt-Hurst|first3=Heather Vaughan|last3=Lee|first4=Mary|last4=Doering|date=23 November 2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books|isbn=9781610693103}}</ref> Beginning in 1920 and especially after World War II, many [[Danube Swabians]] migrated to the United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, Austria, Australia, and Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr |title=bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103 |website=Memoria.ro |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAcross the United States there are dozens of German-American cultural or heritage clubs, such as the Donauschwaben<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-25|title=Danube Swabians|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Danube_Swabians&oldid=761981460|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref> heritage clubs.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In these clubs, members host events and festivals to preserve and/or celebrate their heritage with the surrounding communities. During these festivals, participants often dress in traditional outfits such as dirndls and [[lederhosen]].\n\n==Name==\nIn the South German dialects ([[Austro-Bavarian|Bairisch]]), ''Dirndl'' originally referred to a young woman or a girl, while the word ''Dirndlgewand'' referred to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hCbTfFKEUUgC&pg=PA106|title=Munique e Arredores: Alemanha! Por que n\u00e3o?|first=Angela|last=Arten-Meyer|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Books on Demand|via=Google Books|isbn=9783842359796}}</ref> Nowadays, ''Dirndl'' may equally refer to either a young woman or to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> ''Dirndl'' is a diminutive form of the dated word ''Dirn(e)'' for \"girl\"; in the 20th century, ''Dirne'' (originally a euphemism) has also developed towards meaning \"prostitute\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The word is ''Dirn'' in standardized  German  and ''Deern'' in  Low Saxon.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/>\n\n==Dressing etiquette==\nThe dirndl is mostly worn in [[Austria]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is used as an everyday dress primarily by older women in rural areas. Other women may wear it at formal occasions (much like a [[Scotland|Scotsman]] wearing a [[kilt]]) and during certain traditional events. It is hugely popular also among young women at the time of a ''[[Volksfest]]'', such as the [[Oktoberfest]] in [[Munich]] (and similar festivals),<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/> although many women will only wear dirndl-style dresses, called ''Landhausmode'', which may deviate in numerous ways and are often much cheaper.\n\nIn Austria and Bavaria, the dirndl may often be seen on women working in tourism-related businesses, and sometimes waitresses in traditional-style restaurants or [[beer garden]]s. It is also seen in these regions on women in the ''[[Volksmusik]]'' business.\n\nThere is an [[urban legend]] that claims the placement of the [[knot]] on the apron is an indicator of the woman's marital status.<ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/09/germany-oktoberfest-dirndl-fashion/406294/|title=You're Wearing Your Oktoberfest Dress Wrong|last=Horn|first=Heather|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref>  In this story, which is not based in tradition, tying the sash on the woman's left side indicates that she is single, and a knot tied on the right means that she is married, engaged or otherwise not interested in dating.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Dirndl Code: Expert Tips for a Rollicking Oktoberfest|first=Julia|last=Stanek|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/expert-tips-how-to-get-the-most-out-of-oktoberfest-a-922991.html|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=18 September 2013|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|location=Hamburg}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/>\n\n==Films featuring women in dirndl costumes==\n{{see also|Heimatfilm}}\n\n*''[[Almost Angels]]''\n*''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]''\n*''[[Heidi]]'' ([[Heidi (1937 film)|1937]] and [[Heidi (1968 film)|1968]])\n*''[[National Lampoon's European Vacation]]'' \n*''[[The Producers (1967 film)|The Producers]]''\n*''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''\n*''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''\n*''[[The Student Prince]]''\n*''[[The Witch (2015 film)|The Witch]]'' \n*''[[Young Frankenstein]]''\n*''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]''\n\n==Musical mentions of dirndls==\n*The dirndl is mentioned in the song \"Turn Around\", composed in 1959 by [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Alan Greene]], and [[Malvina Reynolds]]. \"Dirndls and petticoats, where have you gone?\"  This song was originally recorded by the [[Kingston Trio]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dirndl}}\n{{portal|Austria|Germany|Switzerland}}\n* [[Pinafore]]\n* [[Pinafore dress]]\n* [[Lederhosen]]\n* [[Tracht]]\n* [[Bild Lilli doll]]\n* [[Folk costume]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gexi Tostmann: ''Das Dirndl (Alpenl\u00e4ndische Tradition und Mode)''. Verlag Christian Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 1998\n* Heide Hollmer, Kathrin Hollmer: ''Dirndl. Trends, Traditionen, Philosophie, Pop, Stil, Styling''. Edition Ebersbach, Berlin 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-86915-043-7}}\n* Daniela M\u00fcller: ''Alles Dirndl.'' Anton Pustet Verlag, Salzburg 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7025-0693-3}}\n* Elisabeth Walln\u00f6fer: ''Geraubte Tradition. Wie die Nazis unsere Kultur verf\u00e4lschten.'' Sankt Ulrich, Augsburg 2011, {{ISBN|3867441944}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Dirndl}}\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n*https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174\n*[http://www.kfj.at/sites/thesite/dirndl.JPG image at an Austrian website]\n*[http://www.oldworldvillage.net/images/heidi/clothing/ladies/dirl3.jpg another image]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/officegeek/45002967/ modern dirndl]\n*[http://www.postrealism.com/dirndl.htm Photo and History of Dirndl Dress and Austrian Tracht]\n*[http://www.elsenaju.de/Mode/Trachten.htm Folk costume]\n*[https://www.mydirndl.com mydirndl.com] \n*[https://www.dirndl.com/en/ dirndl.com]\n*[https://www.oktoberfest.de/en/shop/tracht-for-women/dirndl-dresses/ oktoberfest.de]\n*[https://www.ernstlicht.com/12-ladies-clothing/97-ladies-dirndls ernstlicht.com]\n*[https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174 reference.com]\n\n{{Folk costume}}\n\n[[Category:1870s fashion]]\n[[Category:19th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:German clothing]]\n[[Category:Austrian clothing]]\n[[Category:Swiss clothing]]\n[[Category:Skirts]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:German culture]]\n[[Category:Austrian culture]]\n\n[[bar:Diandl]]\n", "name_user": "Sean Ramsay 3084", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment of the dirndl as a fashion mode", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirndl"}
