{"title_page": "Alnod Boger", "text_new": "{{short description|English cricketer and barrister}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = \n|               image = \n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Alnod John Boger\n|          birth_date = 31 August 1871\n|         birth_place = [[Stonehouse, Plymouth|Stonehouse]], [[Devon]], England\n|          death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1940|6|3|1871|8|31}}\n|         death_place = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|            nickname = \n|              family = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right-arm [[Spin bowling|slow]]\n|                role = \n|               club1 = [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]]\n|               year1 = 1891&ndash;1892\n|             columns = 1\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n|            matches1 = 6\n|               runs1 = 143\n|            bat avg1 = 13.00\n|           100s/50s1 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score1 = 41[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries1 = 474\n|            wickets1 = 9\n|           bowl avg1 = 25.00\n|            fivefor1 = 1\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = 6/63\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n|                date = 9 January\n|                year = 2020\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/9839.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Alnod John Boger''' {{postnominal|JP}} (31 August 1871 \u2013 3 June 1940) was an [[English people|English]] first-class [[cricket]]er and barrister.\n\nThe son of Hext Boger and Blanche Luz Bacon, he was born in August 1871 at [[Stonehouse, Plymouth|Stonehouse, Devon]].<ref name=\"PEER\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p60582.htm |title=Alnod John Boger |publisher=www.thepeerage.com |accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref> He was educated at [[Winchester College]], before going up to [[Magdalen College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/27984.html |title=Player profile: Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> While studying at Oxford, Boger made six appearances in [[first-class cricket]] for [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]] in 1891 and 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He scored a total of 143 runs in his six matches, at an [[bowling average|average]] of 13.00 and a high score of 41 [[not out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class Batting and Fielding For Each Team by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> With his right-arm [[Spin bowling|slow bowling]], he took 9 wickets with best figures of 6 for 63,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class Bowling For Each Team by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> which came against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] on debut in 1891.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3679.html |title=Oxford University v Marylebone Cricket Club, 1891 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He gained a [[Blue_(university_sport)#University_of_Oxford|blue]] in cricket and represented the university in [[golf]] in 1893 and 1894.<ref name=\"OBIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/229832.html |title=Wisden - Obituaries in 1940 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref> After graduating from Oxford, he was [[Call_to_the_bar#England_and_Wales|called to the bar]] as a member of the [[Inner Temple]]. He later served as a [[Justice_of_the_peace#England_and_Wales|justice of the peace]] and was the [[High Sheriff of Cornwall]] in 1925.<ref name=\"PEER\"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33031|date=20 March 1925|page=1951}}</ref> Boger died at [[Oxford]] in June 1940.<ref name=\"OBIT\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The story of General Bacon: being a short biography of a peninsula and Waterloo veteran''. London: Methuen, 1903.\n* ''The road I travelled''. Bristol: Arrowsmith, 1936.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Devon|Cornwall}}\n*{{cricinfo|id=9839}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boger, Alnod}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Plymouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Oxford University cricketers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English justices of the peace]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Cornwall]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer and barrister}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = \n|               image = \n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Alnod John Boger\n|          birth_date = 31 August 1871\n|         birth_place = [[Stonehouse, Plymouth|Stonehouse]], [[Devon]], England\n|          death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1940|6|3|1871|8|31}}\n|         death_place = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|            nickname = \n|              family = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right-arm [[Spin bowling|slow]]\n|                role = \n|               club1 = [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]]\n|               year1 = 1891&ndash;1892\n|             columns = 1\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n|            matches1 = 6\n|               runs1 = 143\n|            bat avg1 = 13.00\n|           100s/50s1 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score1 = 41[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries1 = 474\n|            wickets1 = 9\n|           bowl avg1 = 25.00\n|            fivefor1 = 1\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = 6/63\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n|                date = 9 January\n|                year = 2020\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/9839.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Alnod John Boger''' {{postnominal|JP}} (31 August 1871 \u2013 3 June 1940) was an [[English people|English]] first-class [[cricket]]er and barrister.\n\nThe son of Hext Boger and Blanche Luz Bacon, he was born in August 1871 at [[Stonehouse, Plymouth|Stonehouse, Devon]].<ref name=\"PEER\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p60582.htm |title=Alnod John Boger |publisher=www.thepeerage.com |accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref> He was educated at [[Winchester College]], before going up to [[Magdalen College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/27984.html |title=Player profile: Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> While studying at Oxford, Boger made six appearances in [[first-class cricket]] for [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]] in 1891 and 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He scored a total of 143 runs in his six matches, at an [[bowling average|average]] of 13.00 and a high score of 41 [[not out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class Batting and Fielding For Each Team by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> With his right-arm [[Spin bowling|slow bowling]], he took 9 wickets with best figures of 6 for 63,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27984/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class Bowling For Each Team by Alnod Boger |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> which came against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] on debut in 1891.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3679.html |title=Oxford University v Marylebone Cricket Club, 1891 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2020-01-09 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He gained a [[Blue_(university_sport)#University_of_Oxford|blue]] in cricket and represented the university in [[golf]] in 1893 and 1894.<ref name=\"OBIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/229832.html |title=Wisden - Obituaries in 1940 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref> After graduating from Oxford, he was [[Call_to_the_bar#England_and_Wales|called to the bar]] as a member of the [[Inner Temple]]. He later served as a [[Justice_of_the_peace#England_and_Wales|justice of the peace]] and was the [[High Sheriff of Cornwall]] in 1925.<ref name=\"PEER\"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33031|date=20 March 1925|page=1951}}</ref> Boger died at [[Oxford]] in June 1940.<ref name=\"OBIT\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''The story of General Bacon: being a short biography of a peninsula and Waterloo veteran''. London: Methuen, 1903.\n* ''The road I travelled''. Bristol: Arrowsmith, 1936.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=9839}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boger, Alnod}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Plymouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Oxford University cricketers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English justices of the peace]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Cornwall]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alnod_Boger"}
{"title_page": "Yemaek", "text_new": "{{short description|Ancient Korean tribe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name|\nhangul=\uc608\ub9e5\n|hanja={{linktext|\u6fca|\u8c8a}}\n|rr=Yemaek\n|mr=Yemaek\n}}\n'''Yemaek''' or '''Yamaek''' ({{IPA-ko|jem\u025bk}}) were an ancient tribal group in [[Manchuria].\n==Origin==\nYemaek is believed to be a combination of Ye (\u6fca\u00b7\u7a62\u00b7\u8589) and Maek (\u8c8a\u00b7\u8c89) people of two neighboring cultures.<ref>[http://www.readannals.com/forum/attachments/day_070424/20070425_0a55720a0021f13d79fasdtHv3bNuXuT.pdf \u5173\u4e8e\u4e1c\u5317\u53e4\u4ee3\u53f2\u7814\u7a76\u7684\u51e0\u4e2a\u95ee\u9898]</ref> The main culture is the [[Xituanshan|Seodansan culture]]. He Qiutao (\u4f55\u79cb\u6d9b) said Ye is the short name of [[Buyeo kingdom|Buyeo]].<ref>[http://www.zzsck.com/Article/?875.html \u6c11\u65cf\u63a2\u5e7d\uff1a\u592b\u4f59\u4e0e\u79fd\u8c8a]</ref> Dongye first appears in history as a vassal state of [[Gojoseon]] until its fall to China in 108 BCE.<ref>[http://enc.daum.net/dic100/viewContents.do?&m=all&articleID=b05d1565a]</ref> It was known as the '''Huiyetou''' (\u7a62\u90aa\u982d) state in [[Shuowen Jiezi]].<ref>[http://222.216.4.165:8088/periodical/periodical.articles/hljmzck/hljm2004/0401pdf/040112.pdf the Investigation about the Hui Country]</ref><ref>[http://kanji-database.sourceforge.net/dict/swjz/v22.html \u8aaa\u6587\u89e3\u5b57\u7b2c\u5341\u4e00\u7bc7\u4e0b]</ref> It later became a vassal of the increasingly powerful [[Goguryeo]]. According to the Chinese [[Records of Three Kingdoms]], Ye worshiped tigers,<ref>[[Chen Shou]],''[[Records of Three Kingdoms]]'', Volume 30, ''Weizhi'', Chapter 30, ''Dongyizhuan'', \"\u5e38\u7528\u5341\u6708\u7bc0\u796d\u5929\uff0c\u665d\u591c\u98f2\u9152\u6b4c\u821e\uff0c\u540d\u4e4b\u7232\u821e\u5929\uff0c\u53c8\u796d\u864e\u4ee5\u7232\u795e\"</ref> whereas according to ''[[Erya]]'', Maek means bears. [[Gomnaru]], the capital of [[Baekje]], also means the \"bear port\". Historians suggest tigers and bears may have been [[totems]] worshiped by Ye and Maek tribes.\n\nSeveral history books suggest [[Gojoseon]], the first Korean kingdom in history, was established by the Yemaek.<ref>\ud55c\uad6d\ubbfc\uc871\ubb38\ud654\ub300\ubc31\uacfc(\ud55c\uad6d\ud559\uc911\uc559\uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0 \ud3b8\uc9d1) \ucc38\uc870</ref>\n\n:*In [[Dangun]]'s ancestry legend of [[Gojoseon]] recorded in [[Samguk Yusa]], a tiger and a bear prayed to [[Hwanung]] that they may become human but had to stay in a cave eating only garlic and mugwort, and while the tiger shortly gave up and left the cave, the bear remained and after 21 days was transformed into a woman who later married Hwanung and then gave birth to [[Dangun Wanggeom]],<ref>[[Il-yeon]], ''[[Samguk Yusa]]'', Vol.1, ''Giyi Chapter I'', [http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sy_001r_0020_0020_0020]</ref> which is believed to symbolize combination of Ye and Maek tribes into one Yemaek tribe.<ref>[http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/schooling/328862.html Hankyore, 'Why are Korean more familiar with tigers than with bears?'], Dec 21, 2008</ref>\n:*Tombstone of Yeon Namsan (\uc5f0\ub0a8\uc0b0) found in [[Luoyang]] says Yeon, son of [[Goguryeo]]'s leader [[Yeon Gaesomun]], is a [[Gojoseon|Joseon]] person.<ref>[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-gs_kr_006_0010_0040_0020]</ref>\n:*[[Gojoseon]] is called \"Yemaek Joseon\" in the Chinese [[Records of the Grand Historian]], which says Yemaek Joseon bordered on [[Xiongnu]] around 200 BC.<ref>[[Sima Qian]],''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', Vol.110, ''[[Xiongnu]] Liezhuan'',\"\u8af8\u5de6\u65b9\u738b\u5c07\u5c45\u6771\u65b9\uff0c\u76f4\u4e0a\u7a40\u4ee5\u5f80\u8005\uff0c\u6771\u63a5\u7a62\u8c89\u671d\u9bae\"</ref>\n\n==Language==\n{{Main|Ye-Maek language|Koguryoic languages}}\n\nThere have been some academic attempts to recover Yemaek words based on the fragments of [[toponyms]] recorded in the [[Samguk Sagi]] for the areas once possessed by Goguryeo and Buyeo-Baekje.{{relevance inline|date=September 2019|reason=Those efforts aim to reconstruct Goguryeo, not Yemaek}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAccording to [[Samguk Sagi]], [[Silla]] was established as a confederacy of six clans composed of [[Gojoseon|Joseon]] refugees,<ref>[[Kim Bu-sik]], ''[[Samguk Sagi]]'', ''Silla Bongi'', Vol.1, \"\u5148\u662f\u671d\u9bae\u907a\u6c11\u5206\u5c45\u5c71\u8c37\u4e4b\u9593\u7232\u516d\u6751\"[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sg_001r_0020_0010]</ref> and the Royal Seal of Ye (\uc608\uc655\uc9c0\uc778; \u6fca\u738b\u4e4b\u5370), previously used by [[Buyeo Kingdom|Buyeo]]'s kings, was found in [[Silla]] in 19 AD and presented for King [[Namhae of Silla]].<ref>[[Kim Bu-sik]], ''[[Samguk Sagi]]'', ''Silla Bongi'', Vol.1, \"\u6625\u4e8c\u6708 \u5317\u6e9f\u4eba\u8015\u7530 \u5f97\u6fca\u738b\u5370\u737b\u4e4b\"[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sg_001r_0030_0130]</ref>\n\nThe Yemaek culture can be seen as ancestral to the modern [[Culture of Korea]] as well as to the various kingdoms in Korea and parts of northeastern China.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u7-SCzkMZgAC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=yemaek+koreanic#v=onepage&q=yemaek%20koreanic&f=false|title=Haan (han, Han) of Minjung Theology and Han (han, Han) of Han Philosophy: In the Paradigm of Process Philosophy and Metaphysics of Relatedness|last=Son|first=Chang-Hee|date=2000|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780761818601|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe historian Sang-Yil Kim claims that the Koreanic Yemaek tribe did also influence the early Chinese culture. He suggests that the Yemaek tribe had a large cultural impact on [[East Asia]] and that at least some of the [[Dongyi]] were of proto-Korean origin.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u7-SCzkMZgAC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=yemaek+koreanic#v=onepage&q=yemaek%20koreanic&f=false|title=Haan (han, Han) of Minjung Theology and Han (han, Han) of Han Philosophy: In the Paradigm of Process Philosophy and Metaphysics of Relatedness|last=Son|first=Chang-Hee|date=2000|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780761818601|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Manchuria]]\n* [[History of Korea]]\n* [[List of Korean monarchs]]\n* [[Gojoseon]]\n* [[Buyeo Kingdom|Buyeo]]\n* [[Goguryeo]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Early Korean history]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ancient Korean tribe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name|\nhangul=\uc608\ub9e5\n|hanja={{linktext|\u6fca|\u8c8a}}\n|rr=Yemaek\n|mr=Yemaek\n}}\n'''Yemaek''' or '''Yamaek''' ({{IPA-ko|jem\u025bk}}) were an ancient tribal group in [[Manchuria]. the Yemaek are considered responsible for the formation of Tan'gun's kingdom of Kochoson\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Xu|first= Stella Yingzi|date= 2007|title= That Glorious Ancient History of Our Nation: The Contested Re-readings of \"Korea\" in Early Chinese Historical Records and Their Legacy on the Formation of Korean-ness|location= Ann Arbor|publisher= Proquest|page= 220|isbn=9780549440369|quote= The majority of the Kija Choson and Wiman Choson people were Yemaek, the ancestors of the Korean people|id= {{ProQuest|304872860}}}}</ref> They had ancestral ties to various [[Korea]]n kingdoms including [[Gojoseon]], [[Buyeo Kingdom|Buyeo]], [[Goguryeo]], and tribes including [[Okjeo]], [[Dongye]], Yangmaek (\uc591\ub9e5; \u6881\u8c8a) and Sosumaek (\uc18c\uc218\ub9e5; \u5c0f\u6c34\u8c8a).\n\n==Origin==\nYemaek is believed to be a combination of Ye (\u6fca\u00b7\u7a62\u00b7\u8589) and Maek (\u8c8a\u00b7\u8c89) people of two neighboring cultures.<ref>[http://www.readannals.com/forum/attachments/day_070424/20070425_0a55720a0021f13d79fasdtHv3bNuXuT.pdf \u5173\u4e8e\u4e1c\u5317\u53e4\u4ee3\u53f2\u7814\u7a76\u7684\u51e0\u4e2a\u95ee\u9898]</ref> The main culture is the [[Xituanshan|Seodansan culture]]. He Qiutao (\u4f55\u79cb\u6d9b) said Ye is the short name of [[Buyeo kingdom|Buyeo]].<ref>[http://www.zzsck.com/Article/?875.html \u6c11\u65cf\u63a2\u5e7d\uff1a\u592b\u4f59\u4e0e\u79fd\u8c8a]</ref> Dongye first appears in history as a vassal state of [[Gojoseon]] until its fall to China in 108 BCE.<ref>[http://enc.daum.net/dic100/viewContents.do?&m=all&articleID=b05d1565a]</ref> It was known as the '''Huiyetou''' (\u7a62\u90aa\u982d) state in [[Shuowen Jiezi]].<ref>[http://222.216.4.165:8088/periodical/periodical.articles/hljmzck/hljm2004/0401pdf/040112.pdf the Investigation about the Hui Country]</ref><ref>[http://kanji-database.sourceforge.net/dict/swjz/v22.html \u8aaa\u6587\u89e3\u5b57\u7b2c\u5341\u4e00\u7bc7\u4e0b]</ref> It later became a vassal of the increasingly powerful [[Goguryeo]]. According to the Chinese [[Records of Three Kingdoms]], Ye worshiped tigers,<ref>[[Chen Shou]],''[[Records of Three Kingdoms]]'', Volume 30, ''Weizhi'', Chapter 30, ''Dongyizhuan'', \"\u5e38\u7528\u5341\u6708\u7bc0\u796d\u5929\uff0c\u665d\u591c\u98f2\u9152\u6b4c\u821e\uff0c\u540d\u4e4b\u7232\u821e\u5929\uff0c\u53c8\u796d\u864e\u4ee5\u7232\u795e\"</ref> whereas according to ''[[Erya]]'', Maek means bears. [[Gomnaru]], the capital of [[Baekje]], also means the \"bear port\". Historians suggest tigers and bears may have been [[totems]] worshiped by Ye and Maek tribes.\n\nSeveral history books suggest [[Gojoseon]], the first Korean kingdom in history, was established by the Yemaek.<ref>\ud55c\uad6d\ubbfc\uc871\ubb38\ud654\ub300\ubc31\uacfc(\ud55c\uad6d\ud559\uc911\uc559\uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0 \ud3b8\uc9d1) \ucc38\uc870</ref>\n\n:*In [[Dangun]]'s ancestry legend of [[Gojoseon]] recorded in [[Samguk Yusa]], a tiger and a bear prayed to [[Hwanung]] that they may become human but had to stay in a cave eating only garlic and mugwort, and while the tiger shortly gave up and left the cave, the bear remained and after 21 days was transformed into a woman who later married Hwanung and then gave birth to [[Dangun Wanggeom]],<ref>[[Il-yeon]], ''[[Samguk Yusa]]'', Vol.1, ''Giyi Chapter I'', [http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sy_001r_0020_0020_0020]</ref> which is believed to symbolize combination of Ye and Maek tribes into one Yemaek tribe.<ref>[http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/schooling/328862.html Hankyore, 'Why are Korean more familiar with tigers than with bears?'], Dec 21, 2008</ref>\n:*Tombstone of Yeon Namsan (\uc5f0\ub0a8\uc0b0) found in [[Luoyang]] says Yeon, son of [[Goguryeo]]'s leader [[Yeon Gaesomun]], is a [[Gojoseon|Joseon]] person.<ref>[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-gs_kr_006_0010_0040_0020]</ref>\n:*[[Gojoseon]] is called \"Yemaek Joseon\" in the Chinese [[Records of the Grand Historian]], which says Yemaek Joseon bordered on [[Xiongnu]] around 200 BC.<ref>[[Sima Qian]],''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', Vol.110, ''[[Xiongnu]] Liezhuan'',\"\u8af8\u5de6\u65b9\u738b\u5c07\u5c45\u6771\u65b9\uff0c\u76f4\u4e0a\u7a40\u4ee5\u5f80\u8005\uff0c\u6771\u63a5\u7a62\u8c89\u671d\u9bae\"</ref>\n\n==Language==\n{{Main|Ye-Maek language|Koguryoic languages}}\n\nThere have been some academic attempts to recover Yemaek words based on the fragments of [[toponyms]] recorded in the [[Samguk Sagi]] for the areas once possessed by Goguryeo and Buyeo-Baekje.{{relevance inline|date=September 2019|reason=Those efforts aim to reconstruct Goguryeo, not Yemaek}}\n\n==Legacy==\nAccording to [[Samguk Sagi]], [[Silla]] was established as a confederacy of six clans composed of [[Gojoseon|Joseon]] refugees,<ref>[[Kim Bu-sik]], ''[[Samguk Sagi]]'', ''Silla Bongi'', Vol.1, \"\u5148\u662f\u671d\u9bae\u907a\u6c11\u5206\u5c45\u5c71\u8c37\u4e4b\u9593\u7232\u516d\u6751\"[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sg_001r_0020_0010]</ref> and the Royal Seal of Ye (\uc608\uc655\uc9c0\uc778; \u6fca\u738b\u4e4b\u5370), previously used by [[Buyeo Kingdom|Buyeo]]'s kings, was found in [[Silla]] in 19 AD and presented for King [[Namhae of Silla]].<ref>[[Kim Bu-sik]], ''[[Samguk Sagi]]'', ''Silla Bongi'', Vol.1, \"\u6625\u4e8c\u6708 \u5317\u6e9f\u4eba\u8015\u7530 \u5f97\u6fca\u738b\u5370\u737b\u4e4b\"[http://www.history.go.kr/url.jsp?ID=NIKH.DB-sg_001r_0030_0130]</ref>\n\nThe Yemaek culture can be seen as ancestral to the modern [[Culture of Korea]] as well as to the various kingdoms in Korea and parts of northeastern China.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u7-SCzkMZgAC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=yemaek+koreanic#v=onepage&q=yemaek%20koreanic&f=false|title=Haan (han, Han) of Minjung Theology and Han (han, Han) of Han Philosophy: In the Paradigm of Process Philosophy and Metaphysics of Relatedness|last=Son|first=Chang-Hee|date=2000|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780761818601|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe historian Sang-Yil Kim claims that the Koreanic Yemaek tribe did also influence the early Chinese culture. He suggests that the Yemaek tribe had a large cultural impact on [[East Asia]] and that at least some of the [[Dongyi]] were of proto-Korean origin.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u7-SCzkMZgAC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=yemaek+koreanic#v=onepage&q=yemaek%20koreanic&f=false|title=Haan (han, Han) of Minjung Theology and Han (han, Han) of Han Philosophy: In the Paradigm of Process Philosophy and Metaphysics of Relatedness|last=Son|first=Chang-Hee|date=2000|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=9780761818601|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Manchuria]]\n* [[History of Korea]]\n* [[List of Korean monarchs]]\n* [[Gojoseon]]\n* [[Buyeo Kingdom|Buyeo]]\n* [[Goguryeo]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Early Korean history]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Marsmark11", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yemaek"}
{"title_page": "William Field (minister)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:William Field by Charles Turner.jpg|thumb|William Field]]\n'''William Field''' (6 January 1768 \u2013 16 August 1851) was an English [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] minister.\n\n==Early life==\nField was born at [[Stoke Newington]] on 6 January 1768. John Field, his father, a London medical practitioner, and founder of the [[London Annuity Society]], was a man of property, who married Anne, daughter of Thomas Cromwell, a grocer, and sister of [[Oliver Cromwell]]. Field got a good classical training; while at school he corresponded with his father in Latin. He studied for the ministry first at [[Homerton]], but left that institution for doctrinal reasons soon after the appointment of [[John Fell (tutor)|John Fell]]. In 1788 he entered [[Daventry Academy]] under [[Thomas Belsham]], and left when Belsham resigned (June 1789).\n\n==Religious career==\nField succeeded James Kettle in 1789 as minister of the presbyterian congregation at [[Warwick, Warwickshire]], where he was ordained on 12 July 1790. On this occasion Belsham gave the charge, and [[Joseph Priestley]] preached. Dr. [[Samuel Parr]], who then first met Priestley, attended the service and the ordination dinner. Thus began Field's close intimacy with Parr, a connection fostered by their common devotion to classical studies. Field at once (1791) started a Sunday school (the first in Warwick). This led him into a squabble with some local clergy. Field, who was always ready for a [[pamphlet]] war, issued the first of many productions of his incisive pen, in which the dignity of style, and the profusion of literary and classical illustration, contrast curiously with the pettiness of the disputes. His [[meeting-house]], rebuilt 1780, was fitted with a sloping floor, to improve its quality as an [[auditorium]]; Field excited some comment by surmounting the front of the building with a stone cross. About 1830 he undertook the charge of an old [[Presbyterian]] meeting-house at [[Kenilworth]], conducting afternoon service in addition to his Warwick duties. This meeting-house was rebuilt (1846) by his son [[Edwin Wilkins Field]]. Field remained in active duty for nearly sixty years. He resigned Warwick in 1843, and was succeeded in 1844 by Henry Ashton Meeson, M.D. At Kenilworth he was succeeded in 1850 by John Gordon.\n\n==Teaching career==\nField kept a boarding-school for many years at [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leam]], near Warwick. This led to his publishing some educational manuals, of which the most valuable was his ''Questions on the Gospel History'', recommended in the ''[[The Critical Review|Critical Review]]'' (June 1794) to theological students in the two universities. His history of Warwick and his life of Parr are important works.\n\n==Death and family==\nHe died at Leam on 16 August 1851; a marble slab to his memory was placed in High Street Chapel, Warwick. \n\nBy his wife, Mary (Wilkins), who died at Liverpool on 2 October 1848, aged 64, he had a numerous family. Edwin Wilkins, the eldest, married Mary Sharpe, sister of the geologist [[Daniel Sharpe|Daniel]] and the banker and Egyptologist [[Samuel Sharpe (scholar)|Samuel]] and niece of [[Samuel Rogers]] the man of letters; Horace was an architect. \n\nField was of diminutive stature, with a noble head; his portrait has been engraved. He never forgot the distinction of his Cromwell blood; his extensive correspondence was both erudite and racy; he was a genial host, and his conversation, in spite of his constitutional deafness, was very enjoyable.\n\n==Publications==\nField published a multitude of pamphlets and sermons,\n* \"Letter to the Inhabitants of Warwick,\" &c., 1791, 8vo, \n* \"Letter to the Inhabitants \u2026 of Kenilworth,\" &c., 1848, 12mo.\n\nIn addition to these his chief publications were: \n* ''A Series of Questions \u2026 as a Guide to the Critical Study of the Four Gospels'', &c., 1794, 12mo; second edition, printed 1805; \n::Copies were issued from time to time for private use (with various title-pages), but it was not published till 1846, 12mo, with large introduction\n* [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UjUGAAAAQAAJ&dq=howard%20prisons%20warwick&pg=PA148#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Historical and Descriptive Account of \u2026 Warwick and \u2026 Leamington'', &c., Warwick, 1815, 8vo (anon., \"advertisement\" signed W. F.; plates).] \n* ''Memoirs of the Rev. Samuel Parr, LL.D.'', 1828, 2 vols. 8vo.\n\nField was a frequent contributor of critical and other articles to the ''Monthly Repository'' and ''Christian Reformer''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Field, William}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Field, William}}\n[[Category:1768 births]]\n[[Category:1851 deaths]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from London]]\n[[Category:People from Stoke Newington]]\n[[Category:People from Warwick]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:19th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:Deaf religious workers]]\n[[Category:English Unitarian ministers]]\n[[Category:English Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Deaf people from England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n[[File:William Field by Charles Turner.jpg|thumb|William Field]]\n'''William Field''' (6 January 1768 \u2013 16 August 1851) was an English [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] minister.\n\n==Early life==\nField was born at [[Stoke Newington]] on 6 January 1768. John Field, his father, a London medical practitioner, and founder of the [[London Annuity Society]], was a man of property, who married Anne, daughter of Thomas Cromwell, a grocer, and sister of [[Oliver Cromwell]]. Field got a good classical training; while at school he corresponded with his father in Latin. He studied for the ministry first at [[Homerton]], but left that institution for doctrinal reasons soon after the appointment of [[John Fell (tutor)|John Fell]]. In 1788 he entered [[Daventry Academy]] under [[Thomas Belsham]], and left when Belsham resigned (June 1789).\n\n==Religious career==\nField succeeded James Kettle in 1789 as minister of the presbyterian congregation at [[Warwick, Warwickshire]], where he was ordained on 12 July 1790. On this occasion Belsham gave the charge, and [[Joseph Priestley]] preached. Dr. [[Samuel Parr]], who then first met Priestley, attended the service and the ordination dinner. Thus began Field's close intimacy with Parr, a connection fostered by their common devotion to classical studies. Field at once (1791) started a Sunday school (the first in Warwick). This led him into a squabble with some local clergy. Field, who was always ready for a [[pamphlet]] war, issued the first of many productions of his incisive pen, in which the dignity of style, and the profusion of literary and classical illustration, contrast curiously with the pettiness of the disputes. His [[meeting-house]], rebuilt 1780, was fitted with a sloping floor, to improve its quality as an [[auditorium]]; Field excited some comment by surmounting the front of the building with a stone cross. About 1830 he undertook the charge of an old [[Presbyterian]] meeting-house at [[Kenilworth]], conducting afternoon service in addition to his Warwick duties. This meeting-house was rebuilt (1846) by his son [[Edwin Wilkins Field]]. Field remained in active duty for nearly sixty years. He resigned Warwick in 1843, and was succeeded in 1844 by Henry Ashton Meeson, M.D. At Kenilworth he was succeeded in 1850 by John Gordon.\n\n==Teaching career==\nField kept a boarding-school for many years at [[Royal Leamington Spa|Leam]], near Warwick. This led to his publishing some educational manuals, of which the most valuable was his ''Questions on the Gospel History'', recommended in the ''[[The Critical Review|Critical Review]]'' (June 1794) to theological students in the two universities. His history of Warwick and his life of Parr are important works.\n\n==Death and family==\nHe died at Leam on 16 August 1851; a marble slab to his memory was placed in High Street Chapel, Warwick. \n\nBy his wife, Mary (Wilkins), who died at Liverpool on 2 October 1848, aged 64, he had a numerous family. Edwin Wilkins, the eldest, married Mary Sharpe, sister of the geologist [[Daniel Sharpe|Daniel]] and the banker and Egypotologist [[Samuel Sharpe (scholar)|Samuel]] and niece of [[Samuel Rogers]] the man of letters; Horace was an architect. \n\nField was of diminutive stature, with a noble head; his portrait has been engraved. He never forgot the distinction of his Cromwell blood; his extensive correspondence was both erudite and racy; he was a genial host, and his conversation, in spite of his constitutional deafness, was very enjoyable.\n\n==Publications==\nField published a multitude of pamphlets and sermons,\n* \"Letter to the Inhabitants of Warwick,\" &c., 1791, 8vo, \n* \"Letter to the Inhabitants \u2026 of Kenilworth,\" &c., 1848, 12mo.\n\nIn addition to these his chief publications were: \n* ''A Series of Questions \u2026 as a Guide to the Critical Study of the Four Gospels'', &c., 1794, 12mo; second edition, printed 1805; \n::Copies were issued from time to time for private use (with various title-pages), but it was not published till 1846, 12mo, with large introduction\n* [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UjUGAAAAQAAJ&dq=howard%20prisons%20warwick&pg=PA148#v=onepage&q&f=false ''An Historical and Descriptive Account of \u2026 Warwick and \u2026 Leamington'', &c., Warwick, 1815, 8vo (anon., \"advertisement\" signed W. F.; plates).] \n* ''Memoirs of the Rev. Samuel Parr, LL.D.'', 1828, 2 vols. 8vo.\n\nField was a frequent contributor of critical and other articles to the ''Monthly Repository'' and ''Christian Reformer''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DNB|wstitle=Field, William}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Field, William}}\n[[Category:1768 births]]\n[[Category:1851 deaths]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from London]]\n[[Category:People from Stoke Newington]]\n[[Category:People from Warwick]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:19th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:Deaf religious workers]]\n[[Category:English Unitarian ministers]]\n[[Category:English Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Deaf people from England]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Egypotologist->Egyptologist -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Field_(minister)"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of 19th-century Muslim history", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Timeline of Muslim history}}\n\n==19th century (1801\u20131900) (1215 AH \u2013 1318 AH)==\n* 1803: Seikh [[Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud]] assassinated. [[Shoja Shah|Shah Shuja]] proclaimed [[List of leaders of Afghanistan|King of Afghanistan]].\n* 1804: Uprising under [[Kara\u0111or\u0111e|George Petrovich]] against [[Janissaries|Janissary]] garrison at Belgrade marked beginning of [[Serbian Revolution]].\n* 1804: [[Usman Dan Fodio|Othman dan Fodio]] established [[Fulani Empire|Islamic State of Sokoto]] in Northern Nigeria.\n* 1805: [[Saud bin Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad al Saud|Saud bin Abdul Aziz]] captured [[Medina]] defeating the [[Ottoman Empire]] garrison.\n* 1805: [[Faraizi movement]] launched in [[Bengal]]. \n* 1805: Sultan [[Selim III]] yields to the demand that [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] be appointed [[wali|w\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]].\n* 1806: [[Khanate of Khiva]] came into limelight under the rule of [[Muhammad Rahim Khan]].\n* 1807: [[Selim III]] deposed by [[Janissaries]].\n* 1807: [[Darqawi]] sect revolted against [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] domination. \n* 1807: [[Tunisia]] repudiated suzerainty of [[Algeria]].\n* 1808: [[Alemdar Mustafa Pasha|Bairakdar]], the ''ayan'' of [[Rus\u00e7uk]], having arrived in Constantinople too late to restore Selim III (who had been strangled), installed [[Mahmud II]], the sole surviving member of the Ottoman line.\n* 1811: Birth of Siyyid M\u00edrz\u00e1 'Al\u00ed-Muhammad known as the [[B\u00e1b]], founder of [[B\u00e1b\u00eds|B\u00e1b\u00ed movement]]. [[United Kingdom|British]] occupied [[Indonesia]].\n*1811: [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] has [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluks]] [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)#End of Mamluk power in Egypt|massacred in the Citadel of Cairo]], thereby consolidating his absolute power.\n* 1812: [[Medina]] fell to [[Egyptians]].\n* 1812: [[Treaty of Bucharest (1812)|Treaty of Bucharest]] between [[Ottoman Empire]] and [[Russia]] end a war of 6 years  \n* 1813: [[Mecca]] and [[Taif]] captured by [[Egypt]]ian forces and [[House of Saud|Saudis]] expelled from [[Hejaz]].\n* 1814: [[Iran]] executed treaty of alliance with the [[United Kingdom|British]] known as the [[Definitive Treaty]]. Death of [[Saud bin Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad al Saud|Saud bin Abdul Aziz]]. [[King Othman of Tunisia]] assassinated by his cousin Mahmud.\n* 1816: [[United Kingdom|British]] withdrew from [[Indonesia]] restoring it to the [[Netherlands|Dutch]].\n* 1817: [[Syed Ahmad Khan|Sir Syed Ahmad Khan]] born.\n* 1818: Conclusion of Egypt's seven-year campaign against the [[Wahabis]] in Arabia, who had occupied Mecca and Medina and threatened Syria. As a result, the eastern coast of the Mediterranean fell under Egyptian control.\n* 1821: [[Alexander Ypsilantis]] led Greek insurgents across the river [[Prut]] into ''Danubian Principalities'' on March 6 (n.s.) to begin the [[Greek War of Independence]] against the Ottoman Empire.\n* 1822: Death of [[Maulay Ismail]] in [[Morocco]].\n* 1822: Greek assembly at Epidauros declared Greek independence and drew up an organic statute establishing a parliament and executive directory. \n* 1826: Janissaries massacred by forces loyal to Mahmud II after they revolted following formation of new army corps.\n* 1827: [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] became a preserve of the [[United Kingdom|British]] according to [[Anglo]]-[[Netherlands|Netherland]] treaty in 1824.\n* 1828: [[Russia]] declared war against [[Ottoman Empire]].\n* 1829: [[Treaty of Adrianople (1829)|Treaty of Adrianople]] ends the war [[Russo Turkish war]] 1828\n* 1830: [[France|French]] forces landed near [[Algiers]] and occupied [[Algeria]] ending 313 years rule of [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]].\n* 1831: [[Syed Ahmad Barelvi]] and [[Shah Ismail]] leaders of [[Jihad]] movement in [[India]] fell fighting the [[Sikh]]s in [[Balakot]].\n* 1832: [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]] defeated in the battle of [[Konya]] by [[Egypt]]ian forces. \n* 1831: [[Sayyid Majid bin Said Al-Busaid, 1st Sultan of Zanzibar|Sayyid Said]], King of [[Oman]], shifted his capital to [[Zanzibar]].\n* 1833: At the urging of France, the [[Convention of K\u00fctahya]] ended the [[Egyptian\u2013Ottoman War (1831\u201333)|war between Egypt and the Ottoman Empire]] and provided that the empire grant the sultan of Egypt all of Syria and Adana.\n* 1833: The [[Treaty of H\u00fcnk\u00e2r \u0130skelesi]] established alliance between the Ottoman Empire and Russia and provided that the Ottomans would close the [[Dardanelles]] to any foreign warships at the Russians' request.\n* 1834: [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Abdul Qadir of Algeria]] recognized as ruler of the area under his control by the [[France|French]].\n* 1839: In response to threats by Egyptian [[w\u0101li]] [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] to declare himself independent, an Ottoman army began (March) the invasion of Syria from the Euphrates. It was defeated (June 24) by the [[Egypt]]ians in the [[battle of Nezib]]. On July 1 the Turkish fleet surrendered itself (possibly by an act of treachery) to Muhammad Ali in Alexandria.\n* 1839: The [[Edict of G\u00fclhane|Hatt-\u0131 \u015eerif of G\u00fclhane]] (Supreme Edict of the Rose House) issued by sultan [[Abd\u00fclmecid I]], which began the [[Tanzim\u00e2t]] reforms of the Ottoman Empire.\n* 1840: [[Quadruple Alliance (1815)|Quadruple Alliance]] by the [[Europe]]an powers to force [[Egypt]] to relinquish [[Syria]]. [[United Kingdom|British]] free occupied [[Aden]].\n* 1841: [[Adamawa State, Nigeria|State of Adamawa]] established by Adams adjacent to [[Nigeria]].\n* 1842: [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]], ousted from [[Algeria]] by the [[France|French]]. He crossed over to Morocco. [[Shoja Shah|Shah Shuja]] assassinated ending the Durrani rule in Afghanistan.\n* 1847: [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] surrendred to [[France]] under the condition of safe conduct to a [[Muslim]] country of his choice, but France violated its pledge and sent him as a captive to France.\n* 1849: Death of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt]].\n* 1850: The [[B\u00e1b]] is executed by the [[Persian Empire|Persian]] government. [[T\u00e1hirih]], a renowned poet and staunch advocate of [[B\u00e1b\u00eds|B\u00e1bism]] also executed.\n* 1852: Release of [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] by [[Napoleon III of France|Napoleon III]]. He settled in [[Ottoman Empire]].\n* 1853: After a series of intrigues ostensibly designed to enable it to act as protector of Orthodox Christians in Ottoman territories failed, Russia occupied the [[Danubian Principalities]] of [[Moldavia]] and [[Wallachia]] in March. The Ottoman Empire declared war on Russia in October beginning the [[Crimean War]]. Great Britain and France would declare war on Russia the following March. \n* 1856: [[Ottoman Reform Edict of 1856|Hatt-\u0131 H\u00fcm\u00e2y\u00fbnu]] (the Reform Edict of 1856) is issued on February 18 and constitutes the most important Ottoman reform measure of the nineteenth century. It guaranteed the lives and property of Christians, replaced the heads of churches with a national synod, provided full freedom of conscience and civil participation for adherents to all religions. The edict was forced on the sultan by the British, French and Austrians to forestall a Russian intervention.\n* 1856: [[Treaty of Paris (1856)|Treaty of Paris]] (March 30) ends Crimean War, and admits Turkey into the European concert, whereby its independence and imperial integrity was guaranteed. Russia ceded the mouths of the Danube and Bessarabia, returned Kurs, relinquished its claim as protector of Christians in the Ottoman Empire and agreed to the neutralization of the Black Sea.\n* 1857: [[United Kingdom|British]] captured [[Delhi]] and eliminated [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] rule in [[India]] after 332 years. Last Mughal Emperor [[Bahadur Shah II|Bahadur Shah Zafar]] was exiled to [[Yangon|Rangoon]] in [[Myanmar|Burma]]. This was also the end of 1000 years of Muslim rule over India.\n* 1858: Feudal holdings abolished in the Ottoman Empire.\n* 1859: [[Imam Shamil]] laid down arms before [[Russia]]n forces and the Islamic State of [[Dagestan]] became a Russian province.\n* 1860: [[Maulay Muhammad]] defeated by [[Spain]].\n* 1860: [[Masjid-e-Abu Hurairah]], established in [[Cardiff]], is the first mosque in [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]].\n* 1860: [[Druze#Civil War of 1860|Civil War]] between Syrian [[Druze]]s and [[Maronites|Marionite Christians]] erupted. Authorized by the European Powers, France sent expeditionary force which restored order by June 1861.\n* 1861: Sultan [[Abd-ul-Mejid I]] died and is succeeded by [[Abd\u00fclaziz of the Ottoman Empire|Abd\u00fclaziz]] whose reign (1861-1876) is notable for the rapid spread of western influence (particularly Great Britain and France, allies of the Ottoman Empire during the Crimean War), as evidenced by the first foreign loans, railroad construction, and public debt administration, and the rise of secular liberalism, shown by literary revival, translation of Western literature, rise of Turkish journalism and establishment of universities. \n* 1861: Overthrow of the [[Bambara Empire]] by the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1862: [[Faraizi movement]] fizzled out after the death of [[Dadu Miyan]]. Overthrow of the [[Massina Empire]] by the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1863: [[Ottoman Bank|Banque Imp\u00e9riale Ottoamane]] established to function as Turkey's central bank.\n* 1865: [[Khanate of Kokand]] liquidated by [[Russia]].\n* 1869: [[Jamal al-Din al-Afghani]] exiled from [[Afghanistan]]. He proceeded to [[Egypt]].\n* 1871: [[Tunisia]] recognised [[suzerainty]] of [[Ottoman Empire]] through a [[firman (decree)|firman]].\n* 1873: [[Emirate of Bukhara]] and [[Khanate of Khiva]] made [[protectorate]]s by [[Russia]].\n* 1876: [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]] purchased shares of [[Khediv Ismail]] in the [[Suez Canal|Suez canal]] and got involved in [[Egypt]]ian affairs.\n* 1876: Constitutional monarchy in Ottoman Empire (Turkey)(first phase)\n* 1878: Conference of Berlin. Ottoman Empire loses territories to Russia or Balkan countries  \n* 1878: [[Ottoman Empire]] handed over [[Cyprus]] to [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]].\n* 1879: [[Jamal al-Din al-Afghani]] exiled from [[Egypt]]. [[Treaty of Berlin, 1878|Treaty of Berlin]]. [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] lost 4/5 th of its territory in Europe.\n* 1881: [[France]] invaded [[Tunisia]] and the [[Bey]] acknowledged supremacy of [[France]] as a result of the treaty of Bardo. [[Muhammad Ahmad]] declared himself [[Mahdi]] in northern [[Sudan]].\n* 1882: [[Egypt]] came under [[Military of the United Kingdom|British military]] occupation.\n* 1883: Death of [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] in Damascus.\n* 1885: [[Muhammad Ahmad]] declared free Government of [[Sudan]] under his rule. Death of Mahdi Sudani five months after the occupation of [[Khartoum]].\n* 1890: End of the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1889: [[Shah Jahan Mosque, Woking|Shah Jahan Mosque]] opened in [[Woking]] (England).\n* 1891: [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]] of [[Qadian]] claimed to be the promised Messiah and Imam Mahdi, and thus laid the foundation of the [[Ahmadiyya Movement]] in Islam But All scholars of Muslim world especially Indian announce Ghulam Ahmad as fake personality and latterly Parliament of Pakistan declared followers of ahmadiya movement as non- Muslims.\n* 1895: [[Afghanistan]] got [[Wakhan Corridor]] by an understanding with [[Russia]] and [[British Raj|British India]] making Afghan border touch [[China]]. \n* 1897: State of [[Bagirimi]] occupied by the [[France|French]].\n* 1899: Fall of [[Muhammad Ahmad|Muhammad Ahmad's Mahdi State]] occupied by the [[United Kingdom|British]] and the [[Egypt]]ians jointly. By the end of this century, global Muslim population had grown to 13 percent of the total.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of Muslim history]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of 19th Century Muslim History}}\n[[Category:Timelines of Muslim history|19]]\n[[Category:19th-century Islam| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Timeline of Muslim history}}\n\n==19th century (1801\u20131900) (1215 AH \u2013 1318 AH)==\n* 1803: Seikh [[Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad bin Saud]] assassinated. [[Shoja Shah|Shah Shuja]] proclaimed [[List of leaders of Afghanistan|King of Afghanistan]].\n* 1804: Uprising under [[Kara\u0111or\u0111e|George Petrovich]] against [[Janissaries|Janissary]] garrison at Belgrade marked beginning of [[Serbian Revolution]].\n* 1804: [[Usman Dan Fodio|Othman dan Fodio]] established [[Fulani Empire|Islamic State of Sokoto]] in Northern Nigeria.\n* 1805: [[Saud bin Abdul Aziz bin Muhammad al Saud|Saud bin Abdul Aziz]] captured [[Medina]] defeating the [[Ottoman Empire]] garrison.\n* 1805: [[Faraizi movement]] launched in [[Bengal]]. \n* 1805: Sultan [[Selim III]] yields to the demand that [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] be appointed [[wali|w\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]].\n* 1806: [[Khanate of Khiva]] came into limelight under the rule of [[Muhammad Rahim Khan]].\n* 1807: [[Selim III]] deposed by [[Janissaries]].\n* 1807: [[Darqawi]] sect revolted against [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] domination. \n* 1807: [[Tunisia]] repudiated suzerainty of [[Algeria]].\n* 1808: [[Alemdar Mustafa Pasha|Bairakdar]], the ''ayan'' of [[Rus\u00e7uk]], having arrived in Constantinople too late to restore Selim III (who had been strangled), installed [[Mahmud II]], the sole surviving member of the Ottoman line.\n* 1811: Birth of Siyyid M\u00edrz\u00e1 'Al\u00ed-Muhammad known as the [[B\u00e1b]], founder of [[B\u00e1b\u00eds|B\u00e1b\u00ed movement]]. [[United Kingdom|British]] occupied [[Indonesia]].\n*1811: [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] has [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluks]] [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)#End of Mamluk power i