Shah|Shah Shuja]] assassinated ending the Durrani rule in Afghanistan.\n* 1847: [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] surrendred to [[France]] under the condition of safe conduct to a [[Muslim]] country of his choice, but France violated its pledge and sent him as a captive to France.\n* 1849: Death of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt]].\n* 1850: The [[B\u00e1b]] is executed by the [[Persian Empire|Persian]] government. [[T\u00e1hirih]], a renowned poet and staunch advocate of [[B\u00e1b\u00eds|B\u00e1bism]] also executed.\n* 1852: Release of [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] by [[Napoleon III of France|Napoleon III]]. He settled in [[Ottoman Empire]].\n* 1853: After a series of intrigues ostensibly designed to enable it to act as protector of Orthodox Christians in Ottoman territories failed, Russia occupied the [[Danubian Principalities]] of [[Moldavia]] and [[Wallachia]] in March. The Ottoman Empire declared war on Russia in October beginning the [[Crimean War]]. Great Britain and France would declare war on Russia the following March. \n* 1856: [[Ottoman Reform Edict of 1856|Hatt-\u0131 H\u00fcm\u00e2y\u00fbnu]] (the Reform Edict of 1856) is issued on February 18 and constitutes the most important Ottoman reform measure of the nineteenth century. It guaranteed the lives and property of Christians, replaced the heads of churches with a national synod, provided full freedom of conscience and civil participation for adherents to all religions. The edict was forced on the sultan by the British, French and Austrians to forestall a Russian intervention.\n* 1856: [[Treaty of Paris (1856)|Treaty of Paris]] (March 30) ends Crimean War, and admits Turkey into the European concert, whereby its independence and imperial integrity was guaranteed. Russia ceded the mouths of the Danube and Bessarabia, returned Kurs, relinquished its claim as protector of Christians in the Ottoman Empire and agreed to the neutralization of the Black Sea.\n* 1857: [[United Kingdom|British]] captured [[Delhi]] and eliminated [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] rule in [[India]] after 332 years. Last Mughal Emperor [[Bahadur Shah II|Bahadur Shah Zafar]] was exiled to [[Yangon|Rangoon]] in [[Myanmar|Burma]]. This was also the end of 1000 years of Muslim rule over India.\n* 1858: Feudal holdings abolished in the Ottoman Empire.\n* 1859: [[Imam Shamil]] laid down arms before [[Russia]]n forces and the Islamic State of [[Dagestan]] became a Russian province.\n* 1860: [[Maulay Muhammad]] defeated by [[Spain]].\n* 1860: [[Masjid-e-Abu Hurairah]], established in [[Cardiff]], is the first mosque in [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]].\n* 1860: [[Druze#Civil War of 1860|Civil War]] between Syrian [[Druze]]s and [[Maronites|Marionite Christians]] erupted. Authorized by the European Powers, France sent expeditionary force which restored order by June 1861.\n* 1861: Sultan [[Abd-ul-Mejid I]] died and is succeeded by [[Abd\u00fclaziz of the Ottoman Empire|Abd\u00fclaziz]] whose reign (1861-1876) is notable for the rapid spread of western influence (particularly Great Britain and France, allies of the Ottoman Empire during the Crimean War), as evidenced by the first foreign loans, railroad construction, and public debt administration, and the rise of secular liberalism, shown by literary revival, translation of Western literature, rise of Turkish journalism and establishment of universities. \n* 1861: Overthrow of the [[Bambara Empire]] by the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1862: [[Faraizi movement]] fizzled out after the death of [[Dadu Miyan]]. Overthrow of the [[Massina Empire]] by the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1863: [[Ottoman Bank|Banque Imp\u00e9riale Ottoamane]] established to function as Turkey's central bank.\n* 1865: [[Khanate of Kokand]] liquidated by [[Russia]].\n* 1869: [[Jamal al-Din al-Afghani]] exiled from [[Afghanistan]]. He proceeded to [[Egypt]].\n* 1871: [[Tunisia]] recognised [[suzerainty]] of [[Ottoman Empire]] through a [[firman (decree)|firman]].\n* 1873: [[Emirate of Bukhara]] and [[Khanate of Khiva]] made [[protectorate]]s by [[Russia]].\n* 1876: [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]] purchased shares of [[Khediv Ismail]] in the [[Suez Canal|Suez canal]] and got involved in [[Egypt]]ian affairs.\n* 1876: Constitutional monarchy in Ottoman Empire (Turkey)(first phase)\n* 1878: Conference of Berlin. Ottoman Empire loses territories to Russia or Balkan countries  \n* 1878: [[Ottoman Empire]] handed over [[Cyprus]] to [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]].\n* 1879: [[Jamal al-Din al-Afghani]] exiled from [[Egypt]]. [[Treaty of Berlin, 1878|Treaty of Berlin]]. [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] lost 4/5 th of its territory in Europe.\n* 1881: [[France]] invaded [[Tunisia]] and the [[Bey]] acknowledged supremacy of [[France]] as a result of the treaty of Bardo. [[Muhammad Ahmad]] declared himself [[Mahdi]] in northern [[Sudan]].\n* 1882: [[Egypt]] came under [[Military of the United Kingdom|British military]] occupation.\n* 1883: Death of [[Abd al-Qadir al-Jaza'iri|Amir Abdul Qadir]] in Damascus.\n* 1885: [[Muhammad Ahmad]] declared free Government of [[Sudan]] under his rule. Death of Mahdi Sudani five months after the occupation of [[Khartoum]].\n* 1890: End of the [[Toucouleur Empire]].\n* 1889: [[Shah Jahan Mosque, Woking|Shah Jahan Mosque]] opened in [[Woking]] (England).\n* 1891: [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]] of [[Qadian]] claimed to be the promised Messiah and Imam Mahdi, and thus laid the foundation of the [[Ahmadiyya Movement]] in Islam But All scholars of Muslim world especially Indian announce Ghulam Ahmad as fake personality and latterly Parliament of Pakistan declared followers of ahmadiya movement as non- Muslims.\n* 1895: [[Afghanistan]] got [[Wakhan Corridor]] by an understanding with [[Russia]] and [[British Raj|British India]] making Afghan border touch [[China]]. \n* 1897: State of [[Bagirimi]] occupied by the [[France|French]].\n* 1899: Fall of [[Muhammad Ahmad|Muhammad Ahmad's Mahdi State]] occupied by the [[United Kingdom|British]] and the [[Egypt]]ians jointly. By the end of this century, global Muslim population had grown to 13 percent of the total.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of Muslim history]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline Of 19th Century Muslim History}}\n[[Category:Timelines of Muslim history|19]]\n[[Category:19th-century Islam| ]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Egytptian->Egyptian -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_19th-century_Muslim_history"}
{"title_page": "Greta Berlin", "text_new": "{{COI|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Greta Berlin\n|image = Greta Berlin.jpg\n|image_size = 220px\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1941|4|6}}\n|birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]\n|nationality = [[United States of America|American]]\n|occupation = [[State of Palestine|pro-Palestinian]] activist\n| education     = \n| years_active  = \n}}'''Greta K. Berlin''' (born April 6, 1941)<ref>''U.S. Public Records Index'', Vol 1 (Provo, UT: Ancestry.com Operations, Inc.), 2010.</ref> is an American [[State of Palestine|pro-Palestinian]] activist. She has been a spokesperson for the [[Free Gaza Movement]] (FGM), which she co-founded in 2006.\n\n==Biography==\nBerlin was born Greta Anne Hughes on April 6, 1941 in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], the oldest of four children of Arthur George Hughes and Barbara Esther Whan Hughes. She graduated from Culver Military Academy in Culver, Indiana, one of the first two girls to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culvergrads.com/base/alumni/alumni.aspx?id=855&cid=deeld56bav |title=Culver Military Academy Alumni Class of 1959 |publisher=CulverGrads.com|date= |author= |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon entering graduate school at the University of Illinois in 1963, Greta met her first husband, Ribhi, who is a [[Palestinian refugee]] from [[Safed]]. They married in Chicago in 1963 and have a daughter and a son.<ref name=\"WRMEA\">Pat McDonnel Twair, [http://www.wrmea.org/component/content/archive.html?year=2004&month=10 Media Pro Greta Berlin Will Show Her Power Point Presentation Anywhere in U.S.], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], October 2004, ''accessed November 11, 2012.]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://culverahs.com/historygallery/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/citizen1963/culver-citizen-1963-12-18.pdf |title=Greta Anne Hughes and Ribbi Kalla Marriage Announced|publisher=The Culver Citizen|date=December 18, 1963|author=  |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> He died in October, 2018. Her second husband, whom she married in Florida in 1978, was Alvin Jay Berlin. They divorced about 14 years later. Berlin, who was Jewish, died in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/headjewincharge/item/tea_with_greta_my_private_meeting_with_co_founder_of_the_free_gaza_movement |title=Tea with Greta: My Private Meeting with the Founder of the Free Gaza Movement |publisher=Jewish Journal |date=March 20, 2014 |author=LiAmi Lawrence |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe founded GKB Associates in 1977, a training and media coaching firm for scientists and engineers wanting to make presentations to conferences around the world, and worked for some of the top engineering firms in the U.S., the Middle and Far East and Europe, before retiring in 2011.<ref name=\"SOSD\">{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Logan|work=U-T San Diego|title=Pro-Gaza spokeswoman is familiar to S.D. media|date=June 3, 2010|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/jun/03/pro-gaza-spokeswoman-is-familiar-to-sd-media|accessdate=June 7, 2010}}</ref> She now volunteer teaches English around the world.<ref>https://www.themarkaz.org/there_is_no_marshall_plan_for_iraq</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\nBerlin has been an \"advocate for justice for the Palestinians since the early 60s.\"<ref name=Harb>Elias F. Harb, [http://salem-news.com/articles/july132010/greta-berlin-eh.php Exclusive Intifada Interview with Greta Berlin -Free Gaza Movement], Salem-News, July 13, 2010.</ref> She was motivated to activism in 1967 by the [[Six-Day War]]. She believed that \"Israel was driving the Palestinians off their land for the second time in 19 years\" and she vowed to increase American awareness of the issue. Berlin and her husband started a non-profit charitable organization, Pal Aid International to send medicine and aid to the Palestinians. Berlin told an interviewer that the [[Internal Revenue Service]] began auditing her husband's company and that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] began questioning them. She alleged that the [[Jewish Defense League]] phoned her and she described the caller as saying that \"if any passengers were murdered in the airline hijackings that were going on at the time, my children would be killed.\" She withdrew from her activism for 15 years for the sake of her children.<ref name=\"WRMEA\"/>\n\nIn 2003, after the death of [[Rachel Corrie]] who had been working with the [[International Solidarity Movement]] (ISM), Berlin joined ISM and went to Israel, working in Bil\u2019in, Jenin, Ramallah, including in the ISM media office.<ref>[http://www.abc.nl/frontpage/events/index.php?show=details&place=abc&event=802 Book Presentation: Freedom Sailors - Greta Berlin]</ref>\n\n==Free Gaza voyages==\nIn 2006 she co-founded the Free Gaza Movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hadjicostis|first=Menelaos |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Fox News]]|title=Californian-born Free Gaza group to continue aid missions despite deadly Israeli raid|date=June 4, 2010|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/06/04/californian-born-free-gaza-group-continue-aid-missions-despite-deadly-israeli/|accessdate=October 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Interview: 'We Are Not Terrorists,' Gaza Activist Says |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_We_Are_Not_Terrorists_Gaza_Activist_Says/2058141.html|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|accessdate=9 July 2010}}</ref> and was the major spokesperson for the flotilla involved in the [[Gaza flotilla raid]] on May 31, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/world/middleeast/01flotilla.html|work=The New York Times|title=Deadly Israeli Raid Draws Condemnation|first=Isabel|last=Kershner|date=May 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h7yTcRCKr5mtD5AryuuEGVT_sySg Gaza aid fleet undeterred as Israel steps up warnings], [[Agence France-Presse]], May 27, 2010.</ref>\n\nShe was one of the primary spokespersons for Freedom Flotilla 1, a coalition of initiatives put together by Free Gaza to sail a flotilla of boats into Gaza after the ''Dignity'' and the ''Spirit of Humanity'' had been stopped by Israeli naval vessels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/dec/30/israel-gaza-aid-ship|title=Israel accused of ramming Free Gaza Movement aid boat|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2008-12-30|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-06-19}}</ref>\n\nShe continues to criticize Israel's blockade of Gaza, and claims it is unlawful,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306193|publisher=BBC News|title=ICRC says Israel's Gaza blockade breaks law|date=June 14, 2010}}</ref> that it has persisted for 20 years and that one of the reasons Israel is illegally blockading Gaza is because it's busy \"stealing the natural gas of Gaza.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Freedom Sailors |year=2012 |isbn=9780615654898 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\nGreta Berlin calls Israel an \"illegal entity\" and \"a country founded on terrorism\" and she believes that Congress is \"occupied\" by \"the Israeli lobby.\"<ref name=Harb/>\n\n==Freedom Sailors==\nBerlin is the co-author and co-editor of the 2012 book, ''Freedom Sailors, The Maiden Voyage of the Free Gaza movement and How We Succeeded in Spite of Ourselves.'<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Freedom-Sailors-movement-succeeded-ourselves/dp/0615654894</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2012, Berlin was accused of [[antisemitism]] following a tweet, originating from her Facebook account, and published under the Twitter account of the Free Gaza Movement. The tweet, written by someone else, was titled, \"Zionists operated the concentration camps and helped murder millions of innocent Jews\" and contained a link to a video of that name, a speech by [[conspiracy theorist]] [[Eustace Mullins]] asserting that Zionists collaborated with the Nazis.<ref>{{cite web |author=Benjamin Weinthal |title=Free Gaza Group: Zionists Ran Concentration Camps |date=October 4, 2012 |work=The Jerusalem Post |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=286682 |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=JTA2012>{{cite web |title=Flotilla Sponsor Tweets that Zionists Helped Perpetrate the Holocaust |date=October 4, 2012 |publisher=JTA |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/israel/article/flotilla_sponsor_tweets_that_zionists_helped_perpetrate_the_holocaust |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref> The Free Gaza Movement later deleted the tweet. Berlin apologized once the post became known to a wider audience. She declared that she had \"shared it without watching it.\"<ref name=hopper>{{cite web |author=Tristin Hopper |title=Free Gaza Group: Zionists Ran Concentration Camps |date=October 4, 2012 |work=[[National Post]] |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/10/04/gaza-flotilla-sponsor-blames-jews-for-holocaust-on-twitter/ |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe said she merely intended to post the video and comment in a private Facebook group where she had been participating in a discussion of similar propaganda.<ref name=derfner>{{cite web |author=Larry Derfner |title=Head of Free Gaza Movement: Anti-Semitic Video In Question is 'Disgusting' |date=October 6, 2012 |publisher=972 |url=http://972mag.com/head-of-free-gaza-movement-anti-semitic-video-in-question-is-disgusting/57188/ |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref> [[Larry Derfner]] published a statement by sixteen people stating that \"ours is a small and secret Facebook group, 37 members strong\" and that one of the topics the group had been discussing was \"the role of the Zionist movement during the Holocaust\" when Berlin posted her remarks. The statement explained that in this context Berlin's post was aimed at highlighting that \"anti-Semitic remarks have exaggerated and distorted\" the arguments of historians on this topic.<ref name=derfner />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berlin, Greta}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gaza flotilla raid]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Detroit]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Greta Berlin\n|image = Greta Berlin.jpg\n|image_size = 220px\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1941|4|6}}\n|birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]\n|nationality = [[United States of America|American]]\n|occupation = [[State of Palestine|pro-Palestinian]] activist\n| education     = \n| years_active  = \n}}'''Greta K. Berlin''' (born April 6, 1941)<ref>''U.S. Public Records Index'', Vol 1 (Provo, UT: Ancestry.com Operations, Inc.), 2010.</ref> is an American [[State of Palestine|pro-Palestinian]] activist. She has been a spokesperson for the [[Free Gaza Movement]] (FGM), which she co-founded in 2006.\n\n==Biography==\nBerlin was born Greta Anne Hughes on April 6, 1941 in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], the oldest of four children of Arthur George Hughes and Barbara Esther Whan Hughes. She graduated from Culver Military Academy in Culver, Indiana, one of the first two girls to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culvergrads.com/base/alumni/alumni.aspx?id=855&cid=deeld56bav |title=Culver Military Academy Alumni Class of 1959 |publisher=CulverGrads.com|date= |author= |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon entering graduate school at the University of Illinois in 1963, Greta met her first husband, Ribhi, who is a [[Palestinian refugee]] from [[Safed]]. They married in Chicago in 1963 and have a daughter and a son.<ref name=\"WRMEA\">Pat McDonnel Twair, [http://www.wrmea.org/component/content/archive.html?year=2004&month=10 Media Pro Greta Berlin Will Show Her Power Point Presentation Anywhere in U.S.], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], October 2004, ''accessed November 11, 2012.]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://culverahs.com/historygallery/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/citizen1963/culver-citizen-1963-12-18.pdf |title=Greta Anne Hughes and Ribbi Kalla Marriage Announced|publisher=The Culver Citizen|date=December 18, 1963|author=  |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>. He died in October, 2018. Her second husband, whom she married in Florida in 1978, was Alvin Jay Berlin. They divorced about 14 years later. Berlin, who was Jewish, died in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/headjewincharge/item/tea_with_greta_my_private_meeting_with_co_founder_of_the_free_gaza_movement |title=Tea with Greta: My Private Meeting with the Founder of the Free Gaza Movement |publisher=Jewish Journal |date=March 20, 2014 |author=LiAmi Lawrence |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe founded GKB Associates in 1977, a training and media coaching firm for scientists and engineers wanting to make presentations to conferences around the world, and she worked for some of the top engineering firms in the U.S. the Middle and Far East and Europe until she retired in 2011.<ref name=\"SOSD\">{{Cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Logan|work=U-T San Diego|title=Pro-Gaza spokeswoman is familiar to S.D. media|date=June 3, 2010|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/jun/03/pro-gaza-spokeswoman-is-familiar-to-sd-media|accessdate=June 7, 2010}}</ref> She now volunteer teaches English around the world <ref>https://www.themarkaz.org/there_is_no_marshall_plan_for_iraq</ref>\n\n==Political activism==\nBerlin has been an \"advocate for justice for the Palestinians since the early 60s.\"<ref name=Harb>Elias F. Harb, [http://salem-news.com/articles/july132010/greta-berlin-eh.php Exclusive Intifada Interview with Greta Berlin -Free Gaza Movement], Salem-News, July 13, 2010.</ref> She was motivated to activism in 1967 by the [[Six-Day War]]. She believed that \"Israel was driving the Palestinians off their land for the second time in 19 years\" and she vowed to increase American awareness of the issue. Berlin and her husband started a non-profit charitable organization, Pal Aid International to send medicine and aid to the Palestinians. Berlin told an interviewer that the [[Internal Revenue Service]] began auditing her husband's company and that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] began questioning them. She alleged that the [[Jewish Defense League]] phoned her and she described the caller as saying that \"if any passengers were murdered in the airline hijackings that were going on at the time, my children would be killed.\" She withdrew from her activism for 15 years for the sake of her children.<ref name=\"WRMEA\"/>\n\nIn 2003, after the death of [[Rachel Corrie]] who had been working with the [[International Solidarity Movement]] (ISM), Berlin joined ISM and went to Israel, working in Bil\u2019in, Jenin, Ramallah, including in the ISM media office.<ref>[http://www.abc.nl/frontpage/events/index.php?show=details&place=abc&event=802 Book Presentation: Freedom Sailors - Greta Berlin]</ref>\n\n==Free Gaza voyages==\nIn 2006 she co-founded the Free Gaza Movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hadjicostis|first=Menelaos |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Fox News]]|title=Californian-born Free Gaza group to continue aid missions despite deadly Israeli raid|date=June 4, 2010|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/06/04/californian-born-free-gaza-group-continue-aid-missions-despite-deadly-israeli/|accessdate=October 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Interview: 'We Are Not Terrorists,' Gaza Activist Says |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_We_Are_Not_Terrorists_Gaza_Activist_Says/2058141.html|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|accessdate=9 July 2010}}</ref> and was the major spokesperson for the flotilla involved in the [[Gaza flotilla raid]] on May 31, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/world/middleeast/01flotilla.html|work=The New York Times|title=Deadly Israeli Raid Draws Condemnation|first=Isabel|last=Kershner|date=May 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h7yTcRCKr5mtD5AryuuEGVT_sySg Gaza aid fleet undeterred as Israel steps up warnings], [[Agence France-Presse]], May 27, 2010.</ref>\n\nShe was one of the primary spokespersons for Freedom Flotilla 1, a coalition of initiatives put together by Free Gaza to sail a flotilla of boats into Gaza after the ''Dignity'' and the ''Spirit of Humanity'' had been stopped by Israeli naval vessels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/dec/30/israel-gaza-aid-ship|title=Israel accused of ramming Free Gaza Movement aid boat|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2008-12-30|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-06-19}}</ref>\n\nShe continues to criticize Israel's blockade of Gaza, and claims it is unlawful,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10306193|publisher=BBC News|title=ICRC says Israel's Gaza blockade breaks law|date=June 14, 2010}}</ref> that it has persisted for 20 years and that one of the reasons Israel is illegally blockading Gaza is because it's busy \"stealing the natural gas of Gaza.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Freedom Sailors |year=2012 |isbn=9780615654898 |page=18 }}</ref>\n\nGreta Berlin calls Israel an \"illegal entity\" and \"a country founded on terrorism\" and she believes that Congress is \"occupied\" by \"the Israeli lobby.\"<ref name=Harb/>\n\n==Freedom Sailors==\nBerlin is the co-author and co-editor of the 2012 book, ''Freedom Sailors, The Maiden Voyage of the Free Gaza movement and How We Succeeded in Spite of Ourselves.'<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Freedom-Sailors-movement-succeeded-ourselves/dp/0615654894</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2012, Berlin was accused of [[antisemitism]] following a tweet, originating from her Facebook account, and published under the Twitter account of the Free Gaza Movement. The tweet, written by someone else, was titled, \"Zionists operated the concentration camps and helped murder millions of innocent Jews\" and contained a link to a video of that name, a speech by [[conspiracy theorist]] [[Eustace Mullins]] asserting that Zionists collaborated with the Nazis.<ref>{{cite web |author=Benjamin Weinthal |title=Free Gaza Group: Zionists Ran Concentration Camps |date=October 4, 2012 |work=The Jerusalem Post |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=286682 |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=JTA2012>{{cite web |title=Flotilla Sponsor Tweets that Zionists Helped Perpetrate the Holocaust |date=October 4, 2012 |publisher=JTA |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/israel/article/flotilla_sponsor_tweets_that_zionists_helped_perpetrate_the_holocaust |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref> The Free Gaza Movement later deleted the tweet. Berlin apologized once the post became known to a wider audience. She declared that she had \"shared it without watching it.\"<ref name=hopper>{{cite web |author=Tristin Hopper |title=Free Gaza Group: Zionists Ran Concentration Camps |date=October 4, 2012 |work=[[National Post]] |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/10/04/gaza-flotilla-sponsor-blames-jews-for-holocaust-on-twitter/ |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe said she merely intended to post the video and comment in a private Facebook group where she had been participating in a discussion of similar propaganda.<ref name=derfner>{{cite web |author=Larry Derfner |title=Head of Free Gaza Movement: Anti-Semitic Video In Question is 'Disgusting' |date=October 6, 2012 |publisher=972 |url=http://972mag.com/head-of-free-gaza-movement-anti-semitic-video-in-question-is-disgusting/57188/ |accessdate=October 7, 2012}}</ref> [[Larry Derfner]] published a statement by sixteen people stating that \"ours is a small and secret Facebook group, 37 members strong\" and that one of the topics the group had been discussing was \"the role of the Zionist movement during the Holocaust\" when Berlin posted her remarks. The statement explained that in this context Berlin's post was aimed at highlighting that \"anti-Semitic remarks have exaggerated and distorted\" the arguments of historians on this topic.<ref name=derfner />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berlin, Greta}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gaza flotilla raid]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Detroit]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greta_Berlin"}
{"title_page": "Jessica Trisko-Darden", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Canadian academic, activist, former model and beauty queen}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name                = Jessica Trisko\n| birth_name          = Jessica Nicole Trisko\n| image= MissEarth2007.jpg\n| caption             = [[Miss Earth 2007]]\n| title               = [[Miss Earth 2007]] <br/> [[Miss Earth Canada]] 2007 <br/> [[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007\n| nationalcompetition = [[Miss Earth Canada]] 2007<br/>(Winner)<br/>[[Miss Earth 2007]]<br/>(Winner)<br/>[[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007<br/>(Top 10 Semi-finalist)\n| birth_place         = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1984|8|20}}\n| education           = [[McGill University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])<br/>[[University of Texas at Austin]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| height              = {{height|m=1.78}}\n| eye_colour           = Hazel\n| hair_colour          = Brown\n}}\n\n'''Jessica Nicole Darden''' n\u00e9e '''Trisko''' (born 1984) is a Canadian academic, activist, former model and beauty queen. She is Assistant Professor of International Affairs at School of International Service at American University and a Jeane Kirkpatrick Fellow at the American Enterprise Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jessicatrisko.com/|title=about|website=www.jessicatrisko.com|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning the [[Miss Earth Canada]] pageant, Trisko represented Canada at [[Miss Earth 2007]] and became the first Canadian to win the [[Miss Earth]] title. She had previously placed in the top ten at [[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Brainy Beauty|date=November 13, 2007|publisher=Kitchener-Waterloo Record|page=C2|last=The Canadian Press}}</ref> She was a guest judge in the final Miss Earth United States 2016 pageant[[Washington, D.C.|.]]\n\nShe studies the impact of foreign aid on repression and civil war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dissertation|publisher=McGill University|first=Jessica|last=Trisko}}</ref> She has written and published journals on social science, humanities, and international security which were used in various international conferences.<ref name=queens-author>{{cite news|last=Lo|first=Ricardo F.|title=25 Beauty Queens Turned Authors|url=http://www.philstar.com/funfare/article.aspx?articleid=713118&publicationsubcategoryid=70|accessdate=October 18, 2012|newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=August 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130211441/http://www.philstar.com/funfare/article.aspx?articleid=713118&publicationsubcategoryid=70|archive-date=January 30, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRaised in Vancouver, Trisko moved to [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] to attend [[McGill University]] where she excelled as a student-athlete and obtained a Joint Honours Bachelor of Arts degree in 2004. She later lived in the United States and Russia while completing a Master of Arts degree from the [[University of Texas at Austin]].\n\nTrisko's father is of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] heritage, and her mother is [[Filipino people|Filipino]].<ref>{{cite news|title=More stunners in Miss Earth '07|last=Adina|first=Armin|date=November 4, 2007|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer}}</ref> Her first language is English, but she also speaks Russian and French.\n\n==Academia==\nTrisko returned to [[Montreal]] to begin a Ph.D. in Political Science at McGill in 2006.<ref name=\"political-science\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/sites/mcgill.ca.politicalscience/files/JNTrisko.pdf|title=Jessica Nicole Trisko|work=Political Science|publisher=[[McGill Tribune]]|accessdate=February 8, 2012}}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name=\"globe\">{{cite news|title=A Beauty Contest with a Conscience|last=Thanh Ha|first=Tu|date=November 12, 2007|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]|page=A2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/22/yehey/opinion/20071222opi4.html|title=Earth beauty in slippers and rubber shoes|last=Fernando|first=Emmanuel Q.|date=December 22, 2007|access-date=January 12, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120080413/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/22/yehey/opinion/20071222opi4.html|archive-date=November 20, 2008|url-status=dead|publisher=[[The Manila Times]], The Manila Times Publishing Corporation}}</ref>\n\nTrisko obtained a Ph.D. in Political Science from McGill University in 2012 was an Assistant Professor of Political Science at the University of Western Ontario.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalscience.uwo.ca/faculty/trisko/index.html|title=Department of Political Science|access-date=March 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113052907/http://politicalscience.uwo.ca/faculty/trisko/index.html|archive-date=January 13, 2013|url-status=dead|publisher=[[University of Western Ontario]]|df=}}</ref> Her research has been funded by the Social Science and Humanities Research Council of Canada (SSHRC) and the McGill-Universite de Montreal Centre for International Peace and Security Studies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/grad/news/|title=Graduate Student News|accessdate=May 23, 2010|publisher=[[McGill Tribune]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211165425/http://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/grad/news|archive-date=December 11, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n \nTrisko has published in edited volumes and the journals Central Asian Survey and the McGill Foreign Affairs Review.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/title~content=g727480839~db=all|title=Central Asian Survey|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Routledge, Taylor & Francis Group}}</ref> She has presented at numerous academic conferences including the International Studies Association 2009 and 2008 conferences, the ISSS/ISAC 2009 conference,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nps.edu/Academics/Centers/CCC/Conferences/recent/ConferenceProgram14Oct.pdf|title=ISSS/ISAC 2009 Conference Program|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=Naval Postgraduate School}}</ref> the Association for the Study of Nationalities 2007 conference, various McGill-Universite de Montreal Research Group in International Security conferences, and the CDAI-CDFAI 2006 conference.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cda-cdai.ca/cdai/uploads/cdai/2009/04/trisko06.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615013927/http://www.cda-cdai.ca/cdai/uploads/cdai/2009/04/trisko06.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 15, 2011|accessdate=May 21, 2010|publisher=CDA-CDAI}}</ref>\n\n==Community involvement==\nTrisko has been participating in charitable fashion shows since the age of 15. In 2001, she teamed up with [[Ford Models]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]] to participate in the behind-the-scenes reality television series Supermodels, which featured eight half-hour episodes.<ref name=\"globe\" /> In 2008, Trisko guest starred on the Filipino television shows \"The Singing Bee\" and \"Sports Unlimited\".\n\nTrisko has hosted numerous environmental events in Asia and North America. She now serves as a mentor to young women interested in pursuing careers in the fashion industry through the organization \"Teens Reacting Effectively aNd Discovering Style (TRENDS)\" - a national fashion and image project by teens, for teens.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trends Fashion - Fashion for Change |url=http://www.trendsfashion.ca/about.php |access-date=May 21, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814143610/http://www.trendsfashion.ca/about.php |archive-date=August 14, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Jessica hosted the inaugural Jack Layton Winter Ball, a fundraiser for cancer research that benefited the Goodman Cancer Research Centre in Montreal. Members of the late Mr. Layton's family were in attendance, including Mike Layton and Olivia Chow, as well as the current Leader of the Opposition Mr. Thomas Mulcair.<ref>{{cite news|title=McGill Alumni News|url=https://www.alumni.mcgill.ca/aoc/events-travel/EventDetails.php?id=MTgzNzM%3D|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental activism==\n[[Image:Miss earth 2007 winner.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Miss Earth 2007]]\nTrisko, together with the executives of [[Carousel Productions]] and the national organizers of Miss Earth Indonesia, attended the Cool Energy Exhibition on December 10, 2007  with the theme: \"Care for the Change\". More than 20 companies, non-government organizations and other groups participated in this exposition held in the Peninsula Island inside the [[Nusa Dua]] resort showcasing displays about [[Conservation biology|wildlife conservation]], energy, and forest preservation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth Takes Part in the UN Convention on Climate Change|publisher=Miss Earth Foundation|first=Lorraine|last=Schuck|date=December 10, 2007}}</ref>\n  \nOn December 13, 2007, Trisko, along with non-governmental organization, [[Conservation International]] and the Indonesian government, led the release of hundreds of [[sea turtles]] at Nusa Dua beach, [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sea turtle hatchlings set free |url=http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20071214.Y08 |publisher=The Jakarta Post |first=Prodita |last=Sabarini |date=December 4, 2007 |access-date=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430105226/http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20071214.Y08 |archive-date=April 30, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTrisko also took part in the [[2007 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in Bali, alongside [[Miss Earth 2004]] [[Priscilla Meirelles]] and [[Miss Earth Water]] 2006 [[Catherine Untalan]] from December 5\u201315, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth in the \"City of the Gods\" |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/08/yehey/life/20071208lif3.html |publisher=The Manila Times Internet Edition |first= |date=December 8, 2007 |access-date=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216185746/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/08/yehey/life/20071208lif3.html |archive-date=February 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTrisko had a chance to visit many countries during her reign, including [[China]], [[Puerto Rico]], and [[Singapore]]. She also went on multiple trips to [[Indonesia]], the [[United States]], [[Vietnam]], [[Philippines]], and [[Canada]], where she met world environmental leaders, and promoted environmental awareness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth 2007 promises to go back to RP after reign|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/11/06/08/miss-earth-2007-promises-go-back-rp-after-reign|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=November 5, 2007|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/jessicatrisko/ Official Jessica Trisko YouTube site]\n*[http://www.missearth.tv/ Official Miss Earth web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100214000418/http://missearthfoundation.org/ Miss Earth Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Chile}} [[Hil Hern\u00e1ndez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth]]\n|years=[[Miss Earth 2007|2007]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Karla Henry]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Riza Santos]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth Canada]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Denise Garrido]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miss Earth 2007 delegates}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders 2007}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders}}\n{{Miss Canada winners in the Grand Slam pageants}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trisko, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth 2007 contestants]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth winners]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian academic, activist, former model and beauty queen}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name                = Jessica Trisko\n| birth_name          = Jessica Nicole Trisko\n| image= MissEarth2007.jpg\n| caption             = [[Miss Earth 2007]]\n| title               = [[Miss Earth 2007]] <br/> [[Miss Earth Canada]] 2007 <br/> [[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007\n| nationalcompetition = [[Miss Earth Canada]] 2007<br/>(Winner)<br/>[[Miss Earth 2007]]<br/>(Winner)<br/>[[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007<br/>(Top 10 Semi-finalist)\n| birth_place         = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1984|8|20}}\n| education           = [[McGill University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])<br/>[[University of Texas at Austin]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n| height              = {{height|m=1.78}}\n| eye_colour           = Hazel\n| hair_colour          = Brown\n}}\n\n'''Jessica Nicole Darden''' n\u00e9e '''Trisko''' (born 1984) is a Canadian academic, activist, former model and beauty queen. She is Assistant Professor of International Affairs at School of International Service at American University and a Jeane Kirkpatrick Fellow at the American Enterprise Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jessicatrisko.com/|title=about|website=www.jessicatrisko.com|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning the [[Miss Earth Canada]] pageant, Trisko represented Canada at [[Miss Earth 2007]] and became the first Canadian to win the [[Miss Earth]] title. She had previously placed in the top ten at [[Miss Universe Canada]] 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Canada's Brainy Beauty|date=2007-11-13|publisher=Kitchener-Waterloo Record|page=C2|last=The Canadian Press}}</ref> She was a guest judge in the final Miss Earth United States 2016 pageant[[Washington, D.C.|.]]\n\nShe studies the impact of foreign aid on repression and civil war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dissertation|publisher=McGill University|first=Jessica|last=Trisko}}</ref> She has written and published journals on social science, humanities, and international security which were used in various international conferences.<ref name=queens-author>{{cite news|last=Lo|first=Ricardo F.|title=25 Beauty Queens Turned Authors|url=http://www.philstar.com/funfare/article.aspx?articleid=713118&publicationsubcategoryid=70|accessdate=18 October 2012|newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=4 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130211441/http://www.philstar.com/funfare/article.aspx?articleid=713118&publicationsubcategoryid=70|archive-date=30 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRaised in Vancouver, Trisko moved to [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] to attend [[McGill University]] where she excelled as a student-athlete and obtained a Joint Honours Bachelor of Arts degree in 2004. She later lived in the United States and Russia while completing a Master of Arts degree from the [[University of Texas at Austin]].\n\nTrisko's father is of [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] heritage, and her mother is [[Filipino people|Filipino]].<ref>{{cite news|title=More stunners in Miss Earth '07|last=Adina|first=Armin|date=2007-11-04|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer}}</ref> Her first language is English, but she also speaks Russian and French.\n\n==Academia==\nTrisko returned to [[Montreal]] to begin a Ph.D. in Political Science at McGill in 2006.<ref name=\"political-science\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/sites/mcgill.ca.politicalscience/files/JNTrisko.pdf|title=Jessica Nicole Trisko|work=Political Science|publisher=[[McGill Tribune]]|accessdate=8 February 2012}}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref name=\"globe\">{{cite news|title=A Beauty Contest with a Conscience|last=Thanh Ha|first=Tu|date=2007-11-12|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]|page=A2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/22/yehey/opinion/20071222opi4.html|title=Earth beauty in slippers and rubber shoes|last=Fernando|first=Emmanuel Q.|date=2007-12-22|access-date=2009-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120080413/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/22/yehey/opinion/20071222opi4.html|archive-date=November 20, 2008|url-status=dead|publisher=[[The Manila Times]], The Manila Times Publishing Corporation}}</ref>\n\nTrisko obtained a Ph.D. in Political Science from McGill University in 2012 was an Assistant Professor of Political Science at the University of Western Ontario.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalscience.uwo.ca/faculty/trisko/index.html|title=Department of Political Science|access-date=2013-03-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113052907/http://politicalscience.uwo.ca/faculty/trisko/index.html|archive-date=2013-01-13|url-status=dead|publisher=[[University of Western Ontario]]|df=}}</ref> Her research has been funded by the Social Science and Humanities Research Council of Canada (SSHRC) and the McGill-Universite de Montreal Centre for International Peace and Security Studies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/grad/news/|title=Graduate Student News|accessdate=2010-05-23|publisher=[[McGill Tribune]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211165425/http://www.mcgill.ca/politicalscience/grad/news|archive-date=2017-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n \nTrisko has published in edited volumes and the journals Central Asian Survey and the McGill Foreign Affairs Review.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/title~content=g727480839~db=all|title=Central Asian Survey|accessdate=2010-05-21|publisher=Routledge, Taylor & Francis Group}}</ref> She has presented at numerous academic conferences including the International Studies Association 2009 and 2008 conferences, the ISSS/ISAC 2009 conference,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nps.edu/Academics/Centers/CCC/Conferences/recent/ConferenceProgram14Oct.pdf|title=ISSS/ISAC 2009 Conference Program|accessdate=2010-05-21|publisher=Naval Postgraduate School}}</ref> the Association for the Study of Nationalities 2007 conference, various McGill-Universite de Montreal Research Group in International Security conferences, and the CDAI-CDFAI 2006 conference.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cda-cdai.ca/cdai/uploads/cdai/2009/04/trisko06.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615013927/http://www.cda-cdai.ca/cdai/uploads/cdai/2009/04/trisko06.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-06-15|accessdate=2010-05-21|publisher=CDA-CDAI}}</ref>\n\n==Community involvement==\nTrisko has been participating in charitable fashion shows since the age of 15. In 2001, she teamed up with [[Ford Models]] and [[L'Or\u00e9al]] to participate in the behind-the-scenes reality television series Supermodels, which featured eight half-hour episodes.<ref name=\"globe\" /> In 2008, Trisko guest starred on the Filipino television shows \"The Singing Bee\" and \"Sports Unlimited\".\n\nTrisko has hosted numerous environmental events in Asia and North America. She now serves as a mentor to young women interested in pursuing careers in the fashion industry through the organization \"Teens Reacting Effectively aNd Discovering Style (TRENDS)\" - a national fashion and image project by teens, for teens.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trends Fashion - Fashion for Change |url=http://www.trendsfashion.ca/about.php |access-date=2010-05-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814143610/http://www.trendsfashion.ca/about.php |archive-date=2010-08-14 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Jessica hosted the inaugural Jack Layton Winter Ball, a fundraiser for cancer research that benefited the Goodman Cancer Research Centre in Montreal. Members of the late Mr. Layton's family were in attendance, including Mike Layton and Olivia Chow, as well as the current Leader of the Opposition Mr. Thomas Mulcair.<ref>{{cite news|title=McGill Alumni News|url=https://www.alumni.mcgill.ca/aoc/events-travel/EventDetails.php?id=MTgzNzM%3D|accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental activism==\n[[Image:Miss earth 2007 winner.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Miss Earth 2007]]\nTrisko, together with the executives of [[Carousel Productions]] and the national organizers of Miss Earth Indonesia, attended the Cool Energy Exhibition on December 10, 2007  with the theme: \"Care for the Change\". More than 20 companies, non-government organizations and other groups participated in this exposition held in the Peninsula Island inside the [[Nusa Dua]] resort showcasing displays about [[Conservation biology|wildlife conservation]], energy, and forest preservation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth Takes Part in the UN Convention on Climate Change|publisher=Miss Earth Foundation|first=Lorraine|last=Schuck|date=2007-12-10}}</ref>\n  \nOn December 13, 2007, Trisko, along with non-governmental organization, [[Conservation International]] and the Indonesian government, led the release of hundreds of [[sea turtles]] at Nusa Dua beach, [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sea turtle hatchlings set free |url=http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20071214.Y08 |publisher=The Jakarta Post |first=Prodita |last=Sabarini |date=2007-12-04 |access-date=2008-12-31 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430105226/http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20071214.Y08 |archive-date=April 30, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTrisko also took part in the [[2007 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in Bali, alongside [[Miss Earth 2004]] [[Priscilla Meirelles]] and [[Miss Earth Water]] 2006 [[Catherine Untalan]] from December 5\u201315, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth in the \"City of the Gods\" |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/08/yehey/life/20071208lif3.html |publisher=The Manila Times Internet Edition |first= |date=2007-12-08 |access-date=2008-12-31 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216185746/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2007/dec/08/yehey/life/20071208lif3.html |archive-date=February 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nTrisko had a chance to visit many countries during her reign, including [[China]], [[Puerto Rico]], and [[Singapore]]. She also went on multiple trips to [[Indonesia]], the [[United States]], [[Vietnam]], [[Philippines]], and [[Canada]], where she met world environmental leaders, and promoted environmental awareness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miss Earth 2007 promises to go back to RP after reign|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/11/06/08/miss-earth-2007-promises-go-back-rp-after-reign|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=2007-11-05|accessdate=2008-12-31}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/jessicatrisko/ Official Jessica Trisko YouTube site]\n*[http://www.missearth.tv/ Official Miss Earth web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100214000418/http://missearthfoundation.org/ Miss Earth Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Chile}} [[Hil Hern\u00e1ndez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth]]\n|years=[[Miss Earth 2007|2007]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Karla Henry]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Riza Santos]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth Canada]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Denise Garrido]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Miss Earth 2007 delegates}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders 2007}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders}}\n{{Miss Canada winners in the Grand Slam pageants}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trisko, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[